\h Census
\toc1 Census
\toc2 Census
\toc3 Cen.
\mt1 Census
\mt3 often called
\mt2 Numbers
\is1 Introduction
\ip The English word ‘Numbers’ relates to the census of Israeli fighting men so we have chosen to rename it as \bk ‘Census’\bk*. (Actually, there are \em two\em* censuses described in this document, but the plural form of the word feels less comfortable to pronounce.) Hebrew readers call this document ‘Bemidbar’ which is the fourth word in the Hebrew text, and means ‘In the wilderness’. Some European and other translations call it ‘The fourth book of Mosheh’ (Moses).
\ip This document tells about the descendants of Yisrael (called ‘Israel’ in older translations) for the forty years after their departure from Mt. Sinai, until they arrived at the eastern edge of the land that God has promised to give them. This document is named after the census that Yahweh ordered Mosheh to take before the Israelis had left Mt. Sinai.
\ip Then the Israelis purified themselves and celebrated their second ‘pass-over’ festival after some forty years had passed.
\ip Also at that time, the second census of fighting men was taken, i.e., a generation later at Kadesh-Barnea at Kanaan’s southern boundary. But from Kadesh-Barnea, none of them entered the land that Yahweh had promised to give them.
\ip When they were still camped east of the Yarden (Jordan) River, two and a half tribes requested to be given territory on that side of the river, although they sent their fighting men ahead with the other tribes to help them conquer Kanaan.
\ip This ‘Census’ document also records how people were often scared and discouraged as they faced hardship, causing them to sometimes rebel against Yahweh and his chosen servant Mosheh who led them. However, Yahweh’s (mostly) patient endurance of their behaviour is told here, and his faithfulness throughout their generations. It reveals Mosheh as an obedient yet humble leader who was devoted both to Yahweh and to the people he had responsibility for.
\iot Main components of this account
\io1 The Israelis prepare to depart from Sinai \ior 1:1–9:23\ior*
\io2 a. The first Israeli census \ior 1:1–4:49\ior*
\io2 b. Various laws and regulations \ior 5:1–8:26\ior*
\io2 c. The second celebration of the messenger’s ‘pass-over’ \ior 9:1-23\ior*
\io1 From Mt. Sinai to Moav (Moab)\ior 10:1–21:35\ior*
\io1 The events in Moav \ior 22:1–32:42\ior*
\io1 The places passed through by the Israelis \ior 33:1-49\ior*
\io1 Warnings before crossing the Yarden (Jordan) river \ior 33:50–36:13\ior*
\rem This is still a very early look into the unfinished text of the Open English Translation of the Bible. Please double-check the text in advance before using in public.
\ie
\c 1
\s1 The first census of the Israelis by Mosheh
\p
\v 1 In April of the year after the Israeli people \add escaped from\add* Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*, Yahweh spoke to Mosheh \add (Moses)\add* in the Sinai wilderness in the \add sacred\add* tent, saying,\x + \xo 1:1-46: \xt Num 26:1-51.\x*
\v 2 “\add Count all the men who are Yisrael’s descendants by their clans and families, being sure to list all their names\add*.
\v 3 \add Only include those\add* who are twenty or older and able \add to be recruited\add* as soldiers. You and Aharon must enrol them into military divisions.
\v 4 \add The leader of each tribe will accompany\add* you.
\p
\v 5 These are the names of the men who will \add assist\add* you:
\li1 Elitsur (Shedeyur’s son) from Reuven,
\li1
\v 6 Shelumiel (Tsuri-Shaddai’s son) from Shimeon \add (Simeon)\add*,
\li1
\v 7 Nahshon (Amminadav’s son) from Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*,
\li1
\v 8 Netanel (Tsuar’s son) from Yissakar \add (Issachar)\add*,
\li1
\v 9 Eliav (Helon’s son) from Zevulun,
\li1
\v 10 Elishama (Ammihud’s son) from Yosef’s son Efrayim,
\li1 Gamliel (Pedahtsur’s son) from Yosef’s son Menashsheh \add (Manasseh)\add*,
\li1
\v 11 Avidan (Gideoni’s son) from Benyamin,
\li1
\v 12 Ahiezer (Ammishaddai’s son) from Dan,
\li1
\v 13 Pagiel (Okran’s son) from Asher,
\li1
\v 14 Elyasaf (Reuel’s son) from Gad,
\li1
\v 15 Ahira (Enan’s son) from Naftali.
\v 16 They were the leaders of their tribes—chosen out of their communities, and leaders of \add units of\add* one thousand \add soldiers\add*.
\p
\v 17 Mosheh and Aharon took those men whose names had been \add given\add*
\v 18 and they assembled the entire community that April. \add For each tribe,\add* they recorded their ancestry by clan, counting the names of those men who were twenty or over,
\v 19 just as Yahweh had commanded Mosheh. \add So\add* he counted them \add there\add* in the Sinai wilderness,
\v 20-21 individually counting those \add in each tribe below\add* by their clan, and only including males who were twenty or older and able to fight in battle:
\li1 46,500 men from the tribe of Reuven,
\li1
\v 22-23 59,300 men from the tribe of Shimeon \add (Simeon)\add*,
\li1
\v 24-25 45,560 men from the tribe of Gad,
\li1
\v 26-27 74,600 men from the tribe of Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*,
\li1
\v 28-29 54,400 men from the tribe of Yissakar \add (Issachar)\add*,
\li1
\v 30-31 57,400 men from the tribe of Zevulun,
\li1
\v 32-33 40,500 men from the tribe of Efrayim,
\li1
\v 34-35 32,200 men from the tribe of Menashsheh \add (Manasseh)\add*,
\li1
\v 36-37 35,400 men from the tribe of Benyamin,
\li1
\v 38-39 62,700 men from the tribe of Dan,
\li1
\v 40-41 41,500 men from the tribe of Asher,
\li1
\v 42-43 53,400 men from the tribe of Naftali.
\p
\v 44 Those were the ones that Mosheh and Aharon and the twelve Israeli leaders (one from each tribe) listed.
\v 45 They were all the \add Israelis\add* who were counted according to their \add ancestry\add*, being men who were twenty or older, and \add capable of going off to battle\add*—
\v 46 603,550 of them in total.
\v 47 \add However,\add* the Levites \add weren’t listed along with the other tribes\add*
\v 48 \add because\add* Yahweh had told Mosheh,
\v 49 “Don’t list the Levites \add or count them with the other Israelis\add*.
\v 50 \add Instead,\add* appoint \add them\add* to manage the tent \add where the copy of the agreement is kept\add*, along with all its equipment. They must serve inside it as \add required\add*, and they should \add set their tents up around it\add*.
\v 51 \add When it’s time to leave that place\add*, the Levites must take \add the tent\add* down and when camp \add is set up\add*, they must erect it \add again\add*, \add but\add* any stranger who approaches it must be \add executed\add*.
\v 52 \add When\add* the \add other\add* \add Israelis\add* set up camp, each man must set up with his army division by their banner,
\v 53 \add but\add* the Levites will camp there around the \add sacred tent\add* and look after it. \add That way,\add* the Israeli community won’t make \add Yahweh\add* angry.
\v 54 \add So the Israelis did everything\add* that Yahweh had instructed Mosheh.
\c 2
\s1 Camp layout by tribe
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh and Aharon:
\p
\v 2 “The \add Israelis\add* must camp \add with each family joining their tribe\add*, \add which will be displaying its\add* banner. They must camp around the \add sacred tent but\add* at a distance.
\p
\v 3 On the eastern side facing the sunrise will be Yehudah’s \add (Judah’s)\add* banner and their army divisions, led by Amminadav’s son Nahshon
\v 4 with 74,600 in his division.
\v 5 The tribe of Yissakar \add (Issachar)\add* will \add set up\add* next to them, led by Tsuar’s son Netanel,
\v 6 with 54,400 in his division.
\v 7 Then the tribe of Zevulun, led by Helon’s son Eliav,
\v 8 with 57,400 in his division.
\v 9 The total number in the divisions in the Yehudah camp is 186,400, and \add when travelling\add*, \add they’ll all go at the front\add*.
\p
\v 10 On the southern side \add of the sacred tent\add* will be Reuven’s banner, led by Shedeyur’s son Elitsur
\v 11 with 46,500 in his division.
\v 12 The tribe of Shimeon \add (Simeon)\add* will \add set up\add* next to them, led by Tsuri-Shaddai’s son Shelumiel
\v 13 with 59,300 in his division.
\v 14 Then the tribe of Gad, led by Reuel’s son Elyasaf.
\v 15 with 45,650 in his division.
\v 16 The total number in the divisions in the Reuven camp is 151,450, and \add when travelling\add*, \add they’ll all go second\add*.
\p
\v 17 Then the Levites will go next with their own banners in the order that they were camped, \add carrying\add* the \add sacred tent\add*.
\p
\v 18 On the western side \add of the sacred tent\add* will be Efrayim’s banner, led by Ammihud’s son Elishama
\v 19 with 40,500 in his division.
\v 20 The tribe of Menashsheh \add (Manasseh)\add* will \add set up\add* next to them, led by Pedahtsur’s son Gamliel
\v 21 with 32,200 in his division.
\v 22 Then the tribe of Benyamin led by Gideoni’s son Avidan
\v 23 with 35,400 in his division.
\v 24 The total number in the divisions in the Efrayim camp is 108,100, and \add when travelling\add*, \add they’ll all go third\add*.
\p
\v 25 On the northern side \add of the sacred tent\add* will be Dan’s banner, led by Ammishaddai’s son Ahiezer
\v 26 with 62,700 in his division.
\v 27 The tribe of Ahser will \add set up\add* next to them, led by Okran’s son Pagiel
\v 28 with 41,500 in his division.
\v 29 Then the tribe of Naftali led by Enan’s son Ahira
\v 30 with 53,400 in his division.
\v 31 The total number in the divisions in the Dan camp is 157,600, and \add when travelling\add*, \add they’ll all go last\add* with their banners.
\p
\v 32 Those are the listed \add Israelis by their ancestral tribes\add* \add with a total of 603,500 fighting men\add*.
\v 33 However, \add following\add* Yahweh’s instructions, the Levites weren’t listed among them.
\p
\v 34 \add So\add* the \add Israelis\add* did everything that Yahweh commanded Mosheh. They camped under their banners, and \add travelled grouped in their tribes and clans\add*.
\c 3
\s1 Aharon’s sons
\p
\v 1 \add The following\add* are the descendants of Aharon \add (Aaron)\add* and Mosheh as on the day when Yahweh spoke with Mosheh on Mt. Sinai:
\v 2 Aharon’s sons were: Nadav (the oldest), Avihu, Eleazar, and Itamar.\x + \xo 3:2: \xt Num 26:60.\x*
\v 3 They were \add all\add* anointed as priests and \add served in that role\add*,
\v 4 \add except that\add* Nadav and Avihu died \add in front\add* of Yahweh when they offered \add unacceptable\add* fire to \add him\add* in the Sinai wilderness, and \add so\add* they had no sons. \add So\add* Eleazar and Itamar served as priests \add alongside\add* their father Aharon.\x + \xo 3:4: \xt Lev 10:1-2; Num 26:61.\x*
\s1 The Levites as ransom for their sons
\p
\v 5 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 6 “Summon the Levites to come and stand in front of Aharon the priest, so they can assist him.
\v 7 They must perform duties for him and for the entire community at and around the \add sacred tent\add*,
\v 8 including looking after all of its equipment and \add fulfilling the obligations\add* of the \add Israelis\add*.
\v 9 You must assign the Levites to Aharon—out of all the \add Israelis\add* it’s them who are assigned \add to serve the priests\add*.
\v 10 Appoint Aharon and his sons as priests and to preserve the priesthood. Any other person \add who tries to act as a priest\add* \add must be executed\add*.”
\p
\v 11 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 12 “Out of all the \add Israelis\add*, I’ve taken the Levites instead of the \add oldest son from every family\add*. The Levites \add will be the ransom for those sons\add*, and so they belong to me,
\v 13 because every firstborn male person and animal is set aside as belonging to me ever since I killed those firstborn males in Egypt. I am Yahweh.”
\s1 The census of the Levites
\p
\v 14 Then in the Sinai wilderness, Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 15 “List all the male Levites that are at least one month old. Count them by their families and clans.”
\v 16 \add So\add* Mosheh listed them exactly as Yahweh had commanded him to,
\v 17 and these were Levi’s sons: Gershon, Kohat, and Merari.
\v 18 Gershon’s sons were: Livni and Shimei.
\v 19 Kohat’s sons were: Amaran, Yitshar, Hevron, and Uzziyel.
\v 20 Merari’s sons were Mahli and Mushi.
\m Those were the families of the Levites by their clans.
\p
\v 21 Gershon’s descendants were the Livnites and the Shimites, so they made up the Gershonites.
\v 22 They had 7,500 males that were at least a month old.
\v 23 The Gershonite clans were to camp on the western side of the \add sacred tent\add*,
\v 24 and \add their\add* leader was Lael’s son Elyasaf.
\v 25 Gershon’s descendants were responsible for the \add sacred tent\add*, including its covering and the entrance curtain,
\v 26 the courtyard curtains, and the courtyard entrance curtain, that surrounded \add it\add*. Also the ropes \add used to hold them\add*.
\p
\v 27 Kohat’s descendants were the Amramites, the Yitsharites, the Hevronites, and the Uzziyelites, so they made up the Kohatites.
\v 28 They had 8,600 males that were at least a month old. They were in charge of the running of the \add sacred tent\add*.
\v 29 The Kohatite clans were to camp of the southern side of the \add sacred tent\add*,
\v 30 and \add their\add* leader was Uzziyel’s son Elitsafan.
\v 31 They were in charge of the box, the table and the lampstand, the altars and all the utensils used for ministry, the \add inside\add* curtain and its gear.
\p
\v 32 The man who organised the Levites was Aharon’s son, Eleazar the priest. He had oversight over all those who were responsible for the \add sacred tent\add*.
\p
\v 33 Merari’s descendants were the Mahlites and the Mushites, so they made up the Merarites.
\v 34 They had 6,200 males that were at least a month old,
\v 35 and their leader was Avihayil’s son Tsuriel. They were to camp on the northern side of the \add sacred tent\add*.
\v 36 \add They\add* were in charge of all the frames for the \add sacred tent\add*, its crossbars, posts, bases, all its containers and equipment,
\v 37 as well as the pillars \add used to make\add* the courtyard with their bases, pegs, and ropes.
\p
\v 38 Mosheh and Aharon and his sons \add set up their tents\add* \add in front of\add* \add the entrance on\add* the eastern side of the \add sacred tent\add*. They were in charge of that tent and \add the needs of\add* the \add Israelis\add*. Any stranger who approached had to be \add executed\add*.
\v 39 Mosheh and Aharon listed 22,000 Levite males that were at least a month old, listing them by their clans as \add per Yahweh’s instructions\add*.
\s1 Paying the price for the firstborn sons
\p
\v 40 Then Yahweh told Mosheh, “List all the \add other\add* male \add Israeli\add* that are at least one month old and \add count them\add*.
\v 41 The Levites are for me, Yahweh, in the place of the firstborn males from every \add Israeli\add* family, and their animals are in place of the \add Israelis’\add* firstborn male animals.”
\v 42 \add So\add* Mosheh listed the firstborn Israelis exactly as Yahweh had commanded him to.
\v 43 and the total number of firstborn males a month old or more whose names were listed came to 22,273.
\p
\v 44 Then Yahweh spoke to Mosheh,
\v 45 “Take the Levites instead of every firstborn male Israeli, and the Levites’ animals instead of their animals, and the Levites will be mine—I am Yahweh.
\v 46 To redeem the 273 firstborn Israelis who outnumber the Levites,
\v 47 collect five silver coins for each one of them. (Use the same silver coins weighing eleven grams, that the priests use in the \add sacred tent\add*.)
\v 48 Give that \add money\add* to Aharon and his sons as payment of the ransom for those excess 273 males.”
\v 49 \add So\add* Mosheh collected that ransom money to cover the ransom of the excess \add not covered by the number of\add* Levites.
\v 50 He collected 1,365 silver coins from the firstborn Israeli males (using the standard weight of silver from the sanctuary)
\v 51 and gave \add it\add* to Aharon and his sons just as Yahweh had commanded.
\c 4
\s1 Kohat’s descendants’ duties
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add* and Aharon \add (Aaron)\add*,
\v 2 “\add Take a detailed census\add* of Kohat’s male descendants by their clans and families
\v 3 \add who are from twenty-five up to fifty years old\add* and who goes into the \add sacred tent\add* to minister.
\p
\v 4 This is what the Kohatites are responsible for concerning the \add sacred tent including the inner room\add*:
\v 5 When \add it’s time to break camp\add*, Aharon and his sons must enter and take down the curtain that veils it, and then use that to cover the box \add containing the agreement\add*.
\v 6 Then they must cover it with \add fine\add* leather, followed by a blue cloth, and then put its \add carrying\add* poles \add through the rings\add*.
\p
\v 7 They must spread a blue cloth over the \add sacred bread table\add*, then place the dishes, pans, bowls, and jugs for the drink offerings on top of that, along with the \add sacred\add* bread.
\v 8 Then they must spread a scarlet cloth over all that, and cover that again with \add fine\add* leather, and then put its poles \add through the rings\add*.
\p
\v 9 They must spread a blue cloth over the lampstand with its \add oil\add* lamps, its tongs and trays, and the oil containers that are used for it.
\v 10 Then they must wrap the lampstand and all its equipment in \add fine\add* leather, and place it \add all\add* on its carrying frame.
\p
\v 11 Then the must spread a blue cloth over the gold \add incense\add* altar, and cover that again with \add fine\add* leather, and then put its poles \add through the rings\add*.
\v 12 Then they must get all the \add other\add* utensils that they use in the \add sacred tent\add*, and cover that again with \add fine\add* leather, and place it \add all\add* on its carrying frame.
\v 13 They need to remove the ashes from the \add bronze\add* altar and spread a purple cloth over it,
\v 14 and put all the utensils they use on top of it: the trays, meat forks, shovel and basins for the altar. Then they must cover it with \add fine\add* leather, and then put its poles \add through the rings\add*.
\v 15 Aharon and his sons must finish covering the \add sacred tent\add* and all its utensils and equipment when \add they’re about to move camp\add*. Then the Kohatites can come to carry it all without touching the \add inner room\add* so they won’t die. That’s the responsibility of Kohat’s descendants—\add carrying\add* the \add sacred tent\add*.
\p
\v 16 Eleazar (son of Aharon the priest) is in charge of the lamp oil and the fragrant incense, the regular grain offering, the anointing oil, and the oversight of the \add sacred tent\add* and the inner room, including everything that’s used inside them.
\p
\v 17 Then Yahweh told Mosheh and Aharon,
\v 18 “Don’t allow the Kohatite Levites to \add get wiped out\add* \add by mishandling the most sacred items\add*,
\v 19 \add but take these precautions on their behalf so\add* they won’t die when they approach the \add most sacred items\add*: Get Aharon and his sons to go and show \add each of them personally\add* the \add correct and proper way to do his duties\add*.
\v 20 \add However,\add* they must never \add go early\add* to \add set their eyes on\add* the \add sacred objects\add*, \add even briefly\add*, or they’ll die.”
\s1 Gershon’s descendants’ duties
\p
\v 21 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 22 “\add Take a detailed census\add* of Gershon’s male descendants by their clans and families
\v 23 \add who are from thirty up to fifty years old\add* and who goes into the \add sacred tent\add* to minister.
\p
\v 24 This is what the Gershonites are responsible for working with and carrying:
\v 25 They must carry the \add inner\add* curtains from the \add sacred tent\add*, the covering, the \add fine\add* leather covering, the entrance curtain,
\v 26 the courtyard curtains, and the courtyard gate curtain, along with the ropes and other equipment for using them. That will be their ministry.
\v 27 Aharon and his sons \add will direct\add* the Gershonites in their duties and assign all \add the items\add* to them.
\v 28 That will be the ministry of Gershon’s descendants with the \add sacred tent\add*, and it will all be under the supervision of Aharon’s son Itamar the priest.
\s1 Merari’s descendants’ duties
\p
\v 29 “\add Take a detailed census\add* of Merari’s descendants by their clans and families,
\v 30 listing the men who are from thirty to fifty years old and who goes into the \add sacred tent\add* to minister.
\v 31 Their duties are carrying the frames, crossbars, posts, and sockets for the \add sacred tent\add*,
\v 32 the courtyard pillars and their bases, their pegs and ropes, and all their equipment. Every man must be assigned by name as to what equipment he must carry.
\v 33 That will be the ministry of Merari’s descendants with the \add sacred tent\add*, and it will all be under the supervision of Aharon’s son Itamar the priest.
\s1 The totals from the Levite census
\p
\v 34 \add So\add* Mosheh and Aharon and the community leaders listed the Kohatites by their clans and families,
\v 35 \add counting\add* the men from thirty to fifty years old who go into the \add sacred tent\add* to minister,
\v 36 and the total for all the clans was 2,750.
\v 37 That was from the Kohatite clans who ministered at the \add sacred tent\add* and were listed by Mosheh and Aharon just as Yahweh had instructed Mosheh.
\v 38 They counted the Gershonites by their clans and families,
\v 39 \add counting\add* the men from thirty to fifty years old who go into the \add sacred tent\add* to minister,
\v 40 and the total for all the clans was 2,630.
\v 41 That was from the Gershonite clans who ministered at the \add sacred tent\add* and were listed by Mosheh and Aharon just as Yahweh had instructed Mosheh.
\v 42 They counted the Merarites by their clans and families,
\v 43 \add counting\add* the men from thirty to fifty years old who go into the \add sacred tent\add* to minister,
\v 44 and the total for all the clans was 3,200.
\v 45 That was from the Merarite clans who ministered at the \add sacred tent\add* and were listed by Mosheh and Aharon just as Yahweh had instructed Mosheh.
\v 46 \add So\add* Mosheh, Aharon, and the Israeli leaders counted \add all\add* the Levites by their clans and families,
\v 47 \add counting\add* the men from thirty to fifty years old who go into the \add sacred tent\add* to minister and also help with carrying it,
\v 48 and the total came to 8,580.
\v 49 Those were the ones counted by Mosheh \add following Yahweh’s instructions\add*. Each man’s name was listed by Mosheh, along with his duties and what was his responsibility to carry.
\c 5
\s1 Handling ceremonial ‘uncleanness’
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*,
\v 2 “Order the \add Israelis\add* that anyone with a skin disease or a discharge, and anyone who’s ‘unclean’ because they touched a corpse, must be sent outside the camp.
\v 3 Whether they’re male or female, they must be sent outside the camp so that the whole camp doesn’t become ‘unclean’ \add because\add* I’m living there \add right\add* amongst them.”
\v 4 \add So the Israelis\add* did what Yahweh told Mosheh, and sent those people outside the camp.
\s1 Reparations for crimes
\p
\v 5 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 6 “Tell the \add Israelis\add* that when any man or a woman \add disobeys God by doing any of the things that humans do\add* when they’re unfaithful towards Yahweh, then that person is guilty
\v 7 and they must confess their \add disobedience\add*. Then that person must make full reparation to whoever they wronged, along with an extra twenty percent \add of the cost\add*.
\v 8 \add However,\add* if reparation to \add the victim isn’t possible\add* \add for some reason\add*, then it must be paid to Yahweh via a priest, in addition to the ram \add that will be offered\add* for that person’s atonement.
\v 9 Any sacred contributions by the \add Israelis\add* that are presented to a priest will belong to him.
\v 10 Each person’s sacred contributions will be their own, \add but\add* anything given to a priest will belong to him.”
\s1 Testing for an unfaithful wife
\p
\v 11 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 12 “Tell the \add Israelis\add* that if any man’s wife \add has an affair\add* and is unfaithful towards him,
\v 13 when another man secretly has sex with her, then she becomes ‘unclean’, even though there’s no witness against her and she wasn’t caught.
\v 14 \add If the husband becomes suspicious, whether or not she’s actually\add* become ‘unclean’,
\v 15 then \add he\add* should take \add her\add* to a priest. He must also bring an offering on her behalf: two litres of barley flour. It must not have any oil or \add spices mixed into it\add* because it’s a grain offering for suspicion—\add for determining if unfaithfulness has occurred\add*.
\p
\v 16 Then the priest must \add lead her forward\add* and stand her in front of Yahweh.
\v 17 He must \add fill\add* a pottery jar with sacred water, and then mix some dust from the floor of \add Yahweh’s\add* residence into the water.
\v 18 Then the priest must stand the woman \add in front\add* of Yahweh and \add let her hair down\add*, then he must place the suspicion grain offering on her palm. (It’s a grain offering for jealousy.) The priest must be \add holding\add* the water of bitterness that brings a curse
\v 19 and tell the woman to make this oath: “If no \add other\add* man \add slept\add* with you, and if you didn’t \add dirty yourself while you’re married\add*, then be free from this water of bitterness that brings a curse.
\v 20 \add But\add* if you \add have cheated on\add* your husband and become ‘unclean’ and slept with some other guy, \add there’ll be consequences\add*.
\v 21 Then the priest will make the woman take that curse as an oath, and \add he’ll\add* tell \add her\add*, “Yahweh will \add make your experience\add* a curse and your people \add will see the results of the\add* oath, when Yahweh gives \add disease to your genitals\add* and makes your belly swell.
\v 22 This water will \add invoke\add* the curse to make your belly swell and your \add genitals shrivel\add*.” Then the woman must say, “Indeed, let it be so.”
\p
\v 23 Then the priest must write those curses on a scroll, then wipe \add the ink\add* into the water of bitterness.
\v 24 He must make the woman drink that water of bitterness that brings the curse, and \add it\add* will enter into her.
\v 25 Then he’ll take the grain offering of suspicion from her hand, and hold it up \add in front\add* of Yahweh, and then take it to the altar.
\v 26 \add He’ll\add* take some of the grain as a memorial portion and burn it on the altar. Then he’ll make the woman drink the water.
\v 27 \add After she’s drunk it\add*, if she was ‘unclean’ and unfaithful to her husband, the water will carry that curse into her, and her belly will swell and her \add genitals will get diseased\add*, and the woman will become a curse among her people.
\v 28 \add However,\add* if she hadn’t defiled herself and is pure, then she’ll be free and \add be able to\add* \add have children\add*.
\p
\v 29 That’s the rule about jealousy when a wife \add cheats on\add* her husband and defiles herself,
\v 30 or when a \add husband\add* \add becomes jealous and suspicious\add* and he stands \add his wife\add* \add in front\add* of Yahweh, and the priest applies this ruling to her.
\v 31 Then \add the husband\add* will be \add innocent\add*, and that women will \add bear the consequences\add* of her wrongdoing.
\c 6
\s1 Instructions for the Nazirite vow
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 2 “Tell the \add Israelis\add* that when any man or woman wants to make a solemn vow to separate themself to Yahweh as a Nazirite,
\v 3 they must keep away from wine and strong drink, and \add even\add* vinegar made from wine or strong drink, plus they mustn’t drink grape juice or eat either grapes or raisins.\x + \xo 6:3: \xt Luk 1:15.\x*
\v 4 For the entire time of their separation, they mustn’t eat anything coming from a grapevine, \add not even\add* the seeds or the skins.
\p
\v 5 “For the entire time of their vow to Yahweh as a Nazirite, they mustn’t cut their hair—they must sacred and grow their hair long.
\p
\v 6 “For the entire time of their separation to Yahweh, they mustn’t approach any dead body,
\v 7 even if it’s their father or mother, or brother or sister. They mustn’t defile themselves with death, because their consecration to their god is on their head.
\v 8 They must remain holy to Yahweh for the whole time.
\p
\v 9 “\add However,\add* if someone right next to them suddenly died, that would defile their consecrated head, and after the \add regular\add* seven days of purification, they would have to shave their head.
\v 10 Then on the eighth day, they’d have to take two doves or young pigeons to the priest at the entrance of the \add sacred tent\add*,
\v 11 and \add he\add* would take one for a sin offering and the other for a burnt offering—making atonement for their transgression with the corpse. Then they would consecrate their head again that day
\v 12 and \add restart\add* their days of separation, as well as bringing a one-year old male lamb as a guilt offering. (Their initial days of separation \add won’t count\add* because they were made ‘unclean’.)
\p
\v 13 “Now these are the instructions for the Nazirites: Once their days of separation are fulfilled, \add someone\add* must take them to the entrance of the \add sacred tent\add*
\v 14 and they will present their offerings to Yahweh—an unblemished, one-year old, male lamb as a burnt offering, and an unblemished, one-year old, female lamb as a sin offering, plus an unblemished ram as a peace/fellowship offering,
\v 15 \add along with\add* a basket of flat breads, flour mixed with oil, and wafers spread with \add olive\add* oil, and their grain and drink offerings.
\v 16 The priest must present all that to Yahweh, and \add handle\add* their sin offering and burnt offering.
\v 17 The ram and the basket of flat breads will be offered as a peace offering to Yahweh, and the priest will offer their grain and wine offerings.
\v 18 Then the Nazirite must shave their head of separation at the opening to the \add sacred tent\add*, and taking the hair, must put it on the fire under their peace offering sacrifice.
\p
\v 19 “The priest will then take the boiled shoulder from the ram, and one flat bread roll and one wafer from the basket, and place them on the palms of that Nazirite with their consecrated head that’s been shaved.
\v 20 Then the priest will raise them as a raised offering to Yahweh. Those raised breads and the shoulder \add are now sacred and belong to\add* the priest. Then the Nazirite can drink some wine.
\p
\v 21 Those are the instructions for the Nazirite who makes a solemn oath to Yahweh for their separation, \add plus what they’re able to give\add*. \add They must do exactly what they promised\add* as per these instructions.”
\s1 The priests’ prayer for blessing
\p
\v 22 Then Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*,
\v 23 “Tell Aharon \add (Aaron)\add* and his sons that when the bless the \add Israelis\add*, this is what they must say:
\q1
\v 24 May Yahweh bless you and protect you.
\q1
\v 25 May \add Yahweh give you prosperity and show grace toward\add* you.
\q1
\v 26 May \add he\add* \add watch over\add* you and give you peace.
\p
\v 27 “\add In that way,\add* they’ll put my name on the \add Israelis\add*, and I will bless them.”
\c 7
\s1 The leaders’ offerings at the altar dedication
\p
\v 1 When Mosheh \add (Moses)\add* had finished setting up the \add sacred tent\add*, he anointed it \add with oil\add* and consecrated it and all its furniture, as well as the altar and all its equipment.
\v 2 Then Yisrael’s leaders presented \add gifts\add*. They were the leaders of the tribes who ruled over those who’d been listed \add for duties\add*.
\v 3 They brought their gifts to Yahweh’s \add presence\add* in six carts \add pulled by\add* twelve bulls. Each cart was from two leaders, and each of the bulls was from one leader.
\v 4 Then Yahweh told Mosheh:
\v 5 “\add Accept their gifts because they’ll be useful for the running of the sacred tent\add*. \add Distribute them appropriately to the Levites, depending on each man’s duties\add*.”
\v 6 \add So\add* Mosheh took the carts and the cattle and distributed them to the Levites,
\v 7 giving two carts and four bulls to the Gershonites to help them with their assigned duties.
\v 8 Then he gave four carts and eight bulls to the Merarites to help them with their assigned duties under the supervision of the priest (Aharon’s son) Itamar.
\v 9 \add However,\add* the Kohaties weren’t given any because they were responsible for carrying the very holy objects, and those had to be carried on their shoulders.
\p
\v 10 The day that the altar was dedicated and anointed, the leaders brought their gifts and presented them at the altar,
\v 11 and Yahweh told Mosheh, “\add Each day\add* \add for the next twelve days\add*, one leader must present his offering for the altar dedication.”
\p
\v 12-83 \add These were the leaders who presented their offerings:\add*
\li1 On the first day, Amminadav’s son Nahshon \add on behalf of\add* the tribe of Yehudah,
\li1 on the second day, Zuar’s son Netanel \add on behalf of\add* the tribe of Yissakar,
\li1 on the third day, Helon’s son Eliav \add on behalf of\add* the tribe of Zevulun,
\li1 on the fourth day, Shedeyur’s son Elitsur \add on behalf of\add* the tribe of Reuven,
\li1 on the fifth day, Tsurishaddai’s son Shelumiel \add on behalf of\add* the tribe of Shimeon,
\li1 on the sixth day, Deuel’s son Elyasaf \add on behalf of\add* the tribe of Gad,
\li1 on the seventh day, Ammihud’s son Elishama \add on behalf of\add* the tribe of Efrayim,
\li1 on the eighth day, Pedahzur’s son Gamaliel \add on behalf of\add* the tribe of Menashsheh,
\li1 on the ninth day, Gideoni’s son Avidan \add on behalf of\add* the tribe of Benyamin,
\li1 on the tenth day, Ammishaddai’s son Ahiezer \add on behalf of\add* the tribe of Dan,
\li1 on the eleventh day, Okran’s son Pagiel \add on behalf of\add* the tribe of Asher,
\li1 and on the twelfth day, Enam’s son Ahira \add on behalf of\add* the tribe of Naftali.
\p \add Each of the leaders presented the following offerings:\add*
\li1 a silver dish (1.5 kg—\add all weights\add* by the standard temple measurement) and a silver bowl (800g)—both of them full of fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering,
\li1 a small gold dish (110g) filled with incense,
\li1 a young bull, a ram and a one-year-old male lamb for a burnt offering,
\li1 a male goat for a sin offering,
\li1 two cows, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old rams for the peace offering.
\p
\v 84 That was the dedication of the altar in the day it was anointed, when Yisrael’s leaders \add presented\add* twelve silver dishes, twelve silver bowls, and twelve gold pans.
\v 85 Each silver dish weighed 1.5kg (\add all weights\add* by the standard temple measurement) and the silver bowls were 800g. The total weight of the silver was around 27 kg.
\v 86 The gold pans that had been filled with incense weighed 110g and their total weight came to 1.3kg.
\v 87 For the burnt offerings there was: twelve bulls, twelve rams, and twelve male one-year-old lambs along with their grain offerings. There were twelve male goats for a sin offering.
\v 88 For the peace offering, there were 24 bulls, 60 rams, 60 male goats, 60 male one-year-old lambs. All of those were part of the dedication offerings for the altar after it was anointed.
\v 89 Then Mosheh entered the \add sacred tent\add* to speak with \add Yahweh\add*. He heard the voice speaking to him from between the two images of winged-creatures that were on the platform above the sacred box. That’s how \add Yahweh\add* spoke to him.
\c 8
\s1 Lighting the seven lamps
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*,\x + \xo 8:1-4: \xt Exo 25:31-40; 37:17-24.\x*
\v 2 “Tell Aharon \add (Aaron)\add* that when he \add places\add* the seven lamps \add on\add* the lampstand, \add they must light up the area in front of it\add*.”
\v 3 \add So\add* Aharon did it just as Yahweh had instructed, setting up the lamps on the lampstand to face forwards.
\v 4 The lampstand from the base to its blossoms had been made by hammering \add a single sheet\add* of gold, just as Yahweh had shown Mosheh.
\s1 The dedication of Levites
\p
\v 5 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 6 “\add Out of all the Israelis\add*, take the Levites and purify them.
\v 7 This is how to make them pure: sprinkle the sin offering water on them, then they must shave their \add entire bodies\add* and wash themselves and their clothes.
\v 8 They must take a \add young\add* bull along with its grain offering of flour mixed with oil, plus a \add second young\add* bull for a sin offering.
\v 9 You must have the Levites stand at the front of the \add sacred tent\add* and summon the rest of the \add Israelis\add* \add there too\add*.
\v 10 Then you must present the Levites \add in front of\add* Yahweh and the \add Israeli men\add* must place their hands on them.
\v 11 \add Out of all the Israelis,\add* Aharon must present the Levites as a raised offering to Yahweh \add so they can serve Yahweh\add* \add with their assigned duties\add*.
\v 12 Then the Levites must place their hands on the bulls’ heads, and one must be given as a sin offering and the other as a burnt offering to Yahweh, to make the Levites \add innocent in Yahweh’s eyes\add*.
\p
\v 13 “The Levites must stand in front of Aharon and his sons, then they can be offered as a raised offering to Yahweh.
\v 14 That’s how \add they’ll\add* be \add distinguished from the other Israelis\add*, and then \add they’ll\add* belong to me.
\v 15 Then the Levites will go to serve at the \add sacred tent\add* after you’ve purified them and presented them as a raised offering,
\v 16 because they’re given to me by all the Israeli people—I’ve taken them for myself in place of their firstborn male sons,
\v 17 because every firstborn Israeli male person and animal belongs to me. I set them apart for myself when I killed every \add other\add* firstborn in Egypt,
\v 18 \add so\add* I’ve \add now\add* taken the Levites instead of the firstborn Israeli sons.
\v 19 Then I’ve given the Levites out of all the Israelis, to Aharon and his sons to serve \add the whole country\add* by serving in the \add sacred tent\add* and making \add the Israelis innocent in Yahweh’s eyes\add*. That way, a plague won’t strike the Israelis when they approach the \add sacred tent\add*.”
\p
\v 20 \add So\add* Mosheh and Aharon and all the \add Israelis\add* did to the Levites \add just\add* what Yahweh had instructed Mosheh.
\v 21 The Levites purified themselves and washed their clothes, and Aharon offered them to Yahweh as a raised offering, and Aharon offered a sacrifice to \add make them innocent in Yahweh’s eyes\add*.
\v 22 After that, the Levites went to do their \add assigned\add* duties at the \add sacred tent\add* \add working under\add* Aharon and his sons. \add The Israelis did exactly what Yahweh told Mosheh to do with\add* the Levites.
\p
\v 23 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 24 “These are the instructions for the Levites: from the age of twenty-five, Levite men will begin serving the work in the \add sacred tent\add*
\v 25 until the age of fifty when they must retire from that work.
\v 26 They may then assist their fellow Levites with guard duties, but they can no longer work \add directly\add* with the \add sacred tent\add*.”
\c 9
\s1 The ‘pass-over’ celebration
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh spoke to Mosheh \add (Moses)\add* in the Sinai wilderness, in the first month of the second year \add after they’d left\add* Egypt,
\v 2 “The \add Israelis\add* must observe ‘pass-over’ at the appointed time.
\v 3 You all must \add celebrate\add* it on the evening of the 14th of this month, \add following all the instructions that you’ve all been given previously\add*.”
\v 4 \add So\add* Mosheh \add ordered\add* the \add Israelis\add* to \add prepare\add* the ‘pass-over’,
\v 5 and they \add celebrated\add* it in the Sinai wilderness \add starting\add* on the evening of the 14th of that first month, \add following all the instructions that Yahweh had given\add* Mosheh.
\p
\v 6 \add However,\add* there were some men who were ‘unclean’ (because they’d touched a dead body) and hence they weren’t able to \add celebrate\add* the ‘pass-over’ that day, \add so\add* they \add approached\add* Mosheh and Aharon
\v 7 and \add asked\add* them, “We were ‘unclean’ because we’d touched a dead body, \add but\add* \add how come we’re excluded\add* from presenting an offering to Yahweh \add along with the other Israelis\add*?”
\p
\v 8 “\add Wait here\add*,” Mosheh \add answered\add*, “and I’ll \add ask\add* Yahweh \add what he wants you all to do\add*.”
\p
\v 9 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 10 “Tell the \add Israelis that\add* for this and future generations, if a person is ‘unclean’ or \add far from home\add*, then they can \add still\add* \add observe\add* Yahweh’s ‘pass-over’.
\v 11 They can \add start\add* it on the evening of the 14th of the \em second\em* month, and eat it \add as usual\add* with flat bread and bitter herbs.
\v 12 They must not break \add any of the lambs bones\add*, must not leave any of it until the morning, and must observe it \add following all the normal instructions\add*.\x + \xo 9:12: \xt Exo 12:46; Yhn 19:36.\x*
\v 13 \add However,\add* any person who isn’t ‘unclean’ or far away, but yet who didn’t celebrate the ‘pass-over’ \add that first month\add*, must be \add driven out of the community\add* and will have to bear their \add own\add* sin.
\p
\v 14 If an \add outsider is living among you\add* and \add celebrates\add* the ‘pass-over’, they must also do it according to \add all the same instructions\add*—\add there’s only one way to do it whether it’s\add* you all, or a foreigner, or a native of the land.
\p
\v 15 \add When the sacred tent was dedicated\add*, the cloud covered the \add inner room of the tent\add*, and \add every evening it would look like fire above\add* the residence, until morning \add came\add*.
\v 16 \add It remained like that\add* continually—the cloud would cover it \add during the day\add*, and then at night, it \add would appear like\add* fire.
\v 17 \add Whenever\add* the cloud \add would be lifted up\add* from the tent, \add then the Israelis\add* would \add leave that place\add*. \add Then\add* wherever the cloud settled down, \add that’s where the Israelis would set up camp\add*,
\v 18 \add so in that way,\add* the \add Israelis would leave a place whenever Yahweh told them, and would set up camp whenever he told them\add*. As long as the cloud stayed above the residence, they would \add stay\add* camped \add in that place\add*.
\v 19 Whenever the cloud remained above the residence for a \add long time\add*, then the \add Israelis\add* would \add follow\add* Yahweh’s \add guidance\add* and wouldn’t \add pack up camp\add*.
\v 20 Sometimes the cloud would only remain above the residence for a few days, in which case they’d \add leave where they’d just camped, and move on as Yahweh commanded\add*.
\v 21 If the cloud was lifted up the next morning, then they’d \add move on\add*—\add in fact\add* whether day or night if the cloud was lifted up, then they would \add move on\add*.
\v 22 Whether it was two days or a month or \add a year\add* that the cloud stayed above the residence, then the \add Israeli\add* camp would remain in that place, until \add eventually\add* \add moving on\add* when it was lifted up \add again\add*.
\v 23 \add In that way,\add* \add when Yahweh ordered them to camp, they would, and when order to move on, they’d do that\add*—thus they \add obeyed\add* Yahweh’s \add instructions to\add* Mosheh.
\c 10
\s1 The silver trumpets
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*,
\v 2 “Make two hammered silver trumpets for yourself to use for \add assembling the community\add* and for \add signalling when it’s time\add* to leave the camp.
\v 3 \add When both are sounded, the whole community is to assemble in front of\add* you at the entrance to the \add sacred tent\add*.
\v 4 \add If just one is sounded,\add* then it’s \add only\add* the leaders and heads of clans who must assemble.
\v 5 A \add single blast\add* means that the camps on the eastern side should \add start\add* moving out.
\v 6 A \add double blast\add* means that the camps on the southern side should \add start\add* moving out. \add So the blasts will signal them to get going\add*.
\v 7 (To assemble the community \add as above\add*, \add use long blows, not short blasts\add*.)
\v 8 The priests (Aharon’s descendants) must be the ones to blow the trumpets. That is a \add permanent\add* regulation.
\p
\v 9 When you \add need to defend yourselves against an attacker\add*, then you must sound an alarm with the trumpets, and you’ll all be \add noticed\add* by Yahweh, and you’ll be saved from your enemies.
\p
\v 10 On festival days and at times of celebrations and at the beginning of each new month, then the trumpets will be blown as the burnt offerings and peace offerings are made as a memorial for you all towards your god. I am your god, Yahweh.
\s1 The Israelis leave Sinai
\p
\v 11 Then on the 20th of the second month in that second year \add (after leaving Egypt)\add*, the cloud was lifted up from above the \add sacred tent\add*
\v 12 and the \add Israelis\add* \add started moving out from the Sinai wilderness as per the pre-arranged order\add*. The cloud moved to the Paran wilderness.
\v 13 That was the first time that they had moved \add as a result of Yahweh signalling Mosheh\add* \add by means of the cloud\add*.
\p
\v 14 Yehudah tribe with their banner \add was the first to leave under the leadership of\add* Amminadav’s son Nahshon.
\v 15 Tsuar’s son Netanel led the company from Yissakar tribe,
\v 16 and Helon’s son Eliav led the company from Zevulun tribe.
\p
\v 17 Then the \add sacred tent\add* was disassembled, and the men of Gershon and Merari set off, carrying the tent.
\p
\v 18 Reuven tribe with their banner \add was next to leave under the leadership of\add* Shedeyur’s son Elitsur.
\v 19 Tsurishaddai’s son Shelumiel led the company from Shimeon tribe.
\v 20 Deuel’s son Elyasaf led the company from Gad tribe.
\p
\v 21 Then the \add sacred utensils\add* were carried out by the Kohatite \add men\add*, who \add then helped set up the sacred tent when they arrived\add*.
\p
\v 22 Efrayim tribe with their banner \add was next to leave under the leadership of\add* Ammihud’s son Elishama.
\v 23 Pedahtsur’s son Gamaliel led the company from Menashsheh tribe.
\v 24 Gideoni’s son Avidan led the company from Benyamin tribe.
\p
\v 25 Dan tribe with their banner \add was last to leave as the rear guard under the leadership of\add* Ammishaddai’s son Ahiezer.
\v 26 Okran’s son Pagiel led the company from Asher tribe.
\v 27 Eynan’s son Ahira led the company from Naftali tribe.
\v 28 That was \add the order of the departures of the companies of the Israeli tribes when they\add* set off.
\p
\v 29 Then Mosheh told Hovav (son of the Midianite Reuel who was Mosheh’s father-in-law), “We’re heading towards the place that Yahweh said he’d give us. Come \add and join us, and we’ll look after you, because Yahweh has promised to look after\add* Yisrael.”
\p
\v 30 “\add Thank you but\add* \add no\add*,” Hovav \add replied\add*, “I’ll \add return\add* to my land and to my relatives.”
\p
\v 31 “Please don’t leave us,” Mosheh \add insisted\add*, “because you’re \add the one who\add* knows about camping in the wilderness, and you \add could be our guide\add*.
\v 32 When you come with us, Yahweh \add will be blessing us so we’ll also bless\add* you.”
\p
\v 33 Then they \add left\add* Yahweh’s mountain \add and travelled for\add* three days, with the box \add containing\add* Yahweh’s agreement \add being carried at the front\add* to find a resting place for them,
\v 34 and Yahweh’s cloud was over them \add each\add* day as they set out from their stop.
\p
\v 35 \add As the box started moving\add*, Mosheh would say, “Yahweh, take action and then your enemies will scatter, and the ones hating you will flee away from your \add presence\add*.”\x + \xo 10:35: \xt Psa 68:1.\x*
\v 36 Then \add at the end of the day\add* when it came to rest, he would say, “Yahweh, return \add to\add* the \add tens of thousands of Israelis\add*.”
\c 11
\s1 Complaints and fire from Yahweh
\p
\v 1 \add One day,\add* the people were complaining \add about their situation\add* and \add when Yahweh heard them, it made him angry\add* \add so he sent a fire that burnt up the edges of their camp\add*.
\v 2 The people cried out to Mosheh \add for help\add*, and \add he\add* prayed to Yahweh, and the fire stopped,
\v 3 and they named that place Taverah \add (which means ‘burning’)\add* because Yahweh’s fire had burnt among them.
\s1 The choosing of seventy elders
\p
\v 4 \add However\add*, there was a \add group of stirrers among the people\add* that \add badly wanted to have meat and other foods to eat\add*. \add That spread to all the Israelis who wept and asked\add*, “Who’ll give us meat to eat?
\v 5 We remember the fish that we ate in Egypt for free, \add as well as\add* the cucumbers, melons, leeks, onions, and garlic,
\v 6 \add but\add* now our appetite \add has shrivelled up because we don’t see anything to eat except this ‘stuff’\add*.”
\p
\v 7 (The ‘stuff’ \add they ate every day\add* was \add a bit\add* like coriander seed \add except kind of clear\add*.\x + \xo 11:7-8: \xt Exo 16:31.\x*
\v 8 \add Each morning\add* the people went around gathering it, then ground it with a \add stone\add* mill or pounded it in a mortar, then they boiled it and made \add something like bread rolls with\add* it. They tasted like fresh \add olive\add* oil.
\v 9 The ‘stuff’ actually descended on the camp during the night with the dew.)\x + \xo 11:9: \xt Exo 16:13-15.\x*
\p
\v 10 Mosheh heard the people weeping in their tents (set up by tribe and clan). \add He\add* thought it was wrong, and \add it made\add* Yahweh \add very angry\add*.
\v 11 \add So\add* Mosheh \add asked\add* Yahweh, “Why \add have you caused me, your servant, to be in trouble\add* \add like this\add*? \add Don’t you approve of me?\add*. \add Why\add* has the burden of all this people group \add landed\add* on me?
\v 12 \add Was it me who\add* conceived \add it\add*? \add Did I carry it to the land promised to their ancestors, like I was a wet-nurse\add*?
\v 13 All these people come to me to ask me to give them meat to eat. Where would I get \add enough\add* meat \add to feed all\add* them?
\v 14 I can’t bear \add the load of\add* this entire people group by myself—it’s too heavy for me.
\v 15 If that’s what you’re doing to me, please kill me now if I’ve found favour in your eyes. \add Then I wouldn’t have to suffer like this\add*.”
\p
\v 16 Then Yahweh told Mosheh, “Bring me seventy of Yisrael’s elders who you know \add are good leaders\add*, and take them to the \add sacred tent\add*, and \add let them take their positions\add* there with you.
\v 17 I’ll come down and talk with you there, and I’ll take some of the spirit that’s on you and put \add it\add* on them, and then they’ll carry the burden of the people along with you. Then you won’t \add have to\add* carry \add it\add* by yourself.
\v 18 \add Also,\add* tell the people that because they wept in my hearing about not having meat to eat like you all did in Egypt, they must \add purify\add* themselves for tomorrow, because I’ll provide meat for you all to eat.
\v 19 You won’t \add just\add* have meat for a day or two, or for five, ten, or twenty days,
\v 20 you have it for a \add whole\add* month until it comes out your nostrils. \add Yes,\add* it’ll make you all nauseous because you rejected Yahweh who’s among you, and you all wept \add in front of him, complaining\add*, ‘Why did we ever leave Egypt?’ ”
\p
\v 21 Mosheh \add queried\add*, “There’s 600,000 \add able to serve in the army\add* \add plus women and children\add*, yet you say that you’ll give them \add all\add* enough meat to eat \add every\add* day for month!
\v 22 \add Even if we killed all the cattle and sheep, or caught all the fish in the sea, that wouldn’t be enough meat\add* for \add all\add* them.”
\p
\v 23 “\add Do you think that\add* Yahweh’s \add powerless\add*?” Yahweh \add replied\add*. “\add Soon\add* you’ll see whether or not my statement will \add come true\add*.”
\p
\v 24 \add So\add* Mosheh went out and \add passed on\add* Yahweh’s message to the people. Then he gathered seventy men from the \add Israeli\add* elders and stood them around the tent.
\v 25 Then Yahweh came down in the cloud and spoke to \add Mosheh\add*, and he took \add some of\add* the spirit away from him and put it on those seventy elders. As the spirit rested on them, they prophesied \add (but they never did that again)\add*.
\p
\v 26 Two of the men who were listed (named Eldad and Meydad), had remained in the \add main\add* camp (not going to the \add sacred\add* tent), and the spirit had \add also\add* rested on them and they prophesied in the camp.
\v 27 A young man ran to Mosheh and told him that Eldad and Meydad were prophesying \add there\add* in the camp.
\p
\v 28 Then Nun’s son Yehoshua (who had helped Mosheh since his youth) \add responded\add*, “My master Mosheh, stop them \add from that\add*.”
\p
\v 29 \add But\add* Mosheh replied, “Are you being jealous \add on my behalf\add*? \add I’d be happy if\add* Yahweh would put his spirit on \em all\em* the people and \add make them into\add* prophets.”
\v 30 Then Mosheh and the elders \add went back to their tents\add*.
\s1 Yahweh sends quails for meat
\p
\v 31 Then Yahweh sent a wind that blew quails from the ocean, and \add they dropped\add* on the ground a day’s walk in every direction around the camp \add until they were piled\add* a metre high.
\v 32 \add So\add* the people went out and collected the quail—\add each family getting at least the equivalent of ten large barrels full\add*, and they spread the meat around the camp \add to sun dry\add*.
\v 33 Then when they started to \add cook and\add* eat \add some of the fresh\add* meat, Yahweh \add got very angry\add* and struck the people with a terrible plague before they could even chew it.
\v 34 \add So\add* that place was named Kivrot-Hattaavah \add (which means ‘Graves of the cravers’)\add*, because that was where they buried the people who had craved \add meat\add*.
\v 35 From Kivrot-Hattaavah, the people \add moved on\add* to Hatserot and \add stayed\add* \add there\add*.
\c 12
\s1 Miryam’s punishment
\p
\v 1 \add One day,\add* Miryam and Aharon spoke out against Mosheh because he’d taken an \add Ethiopian\add* woman (Kushitess) as a wife,
\v 2 and they \add challenged\add*, “Did Yahweh really only speak through Mosheh? Doesn’t he also speak through us?” Yahweh heard \add what they said\add*.
\v 3 (Now Mosheh was \add actually\add* a very humble man—more humble than anyone else \add alive\add*.)
\p
\v 4 Then Yahweh suddenly told Mosheh, Aharon, and Miryam, “Go out, the three of you, to the \add sacred\add* tent.” \add So\add* the three of them went there.
\v 5 and Yahweh descended in a pillar of cloud and stood at the tent opening and called Aharon and Miryam, and the two of them \add stepped forward\add*,
\v 6 and he said, “\add Listen to me\add*. When there’s a prophet of Yahweh, I make myself known to him in a vision and speak to him in a dream,
\v 7 \add but\add* \add I don’t do that to\add* my servant Mosheh. He’s the \add most\add* faithful \add of all my people\add*\x + \xo 12:7 \xt Heb 3:5.\x*
\v 8 \add and\add* I speak to him \add directly\add*—\add face-to-face, and not in parables, and he’s able to see my\add* form. \add So\add* why weren’t you afraid to speak against my servant Mosheh?”
\p
\v 9 \add So\add* Yahweh \add was angry\add* at \add Miryam and Aharon\add*. Then he departed
\v 10 and the cloud \add moved\add* from the tent. Then wow, Miryam had leprosy—her skin had gone as white as snow. As Aharon turned to her, he saw, wow, she was leprous,
\v 11 and \add he\add* \add begged\add* Mosheh, “Please, my master, please don’t \add make us suffer for our foolish disrespect and disobedience\add*.
\v 12 \add Don’t let her be like a still-born baby that’s already starting to decompose when its mother gives birth to it\add*.
\p
\v 13 \add So\add* Mosheh \add pleaded with\add* Yahweh, “God, please, please heal her!”
\p
\v 14 “\add If\add* her father had spit in her face, wouldn’t she \add stay inside in disgrace\add* for seven days?” Yahweh \add replied\add*. “\add So\add* she must be put outside the camp for seven days, then after that, she \add can enter again\add*.”\x + \xo 12:14: \xt Num 5:2-3.\x*
\v 15 \add So\add* Miryam was sent outside the camp for seven days, and the people didn’t \add move on\add* until after she \add was allowed\add* \add to return\add*.
\v 16 After that, the people left Hatserot and set up camp in the Paran wilderness.
\c 13
\s1 Twelve scouts sent into Kanaan
\r (Deu. 1:19-33)
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*,
\v 2 “Send some men in to explore Kanaan—the land that I’m giving to the \add Israelis\add*. Send one man from each \add ancestral\add* tribe—a leader within that tribe.”
\v 3 Then \add at Yahweh’s command\add*, Mosheh sent them off from the Paran wilderness. They were all \add Israeli\add* leaders
\v 4 and their names were:
\li1 Shammua (Zakkur’s son) from Reuven tribe,
\li1
\v 5 Shafat (Hori’s son) from Shimeon tribe,
\li1
\v 6 Kalev \add (Caleb—\add*Yefunneh’s son) from Yehudah \add (Judah)\add* tribe,
\li1
\v 7 Yigal (Yosef’s son) from Yissakar tribe,
\li1
\v 8 Hoshea (Nun’s son) from Efrayim tribe,
\li1
\v 9 Palti (Rafu’s son) from Binyamin tribe,
\li1
\v 10 Gaddiyel (Sodi’s son) from Zevulun tribe,
\li1
\v 11 Gaddi (Susi’s son) from Yosef tribe,
\li1
\v 12 Ammiyel (Gemalli’s son) from Dan tribe,
\li1
\v 13 Setur (Mikael’s son) from Asher tribe,
\li1
\v 14 Nahbi (Vofsi’s son) from Naftali tribe, and
\li1
\v 15 Geuel (Maki’s son) from Gad tribe.
\p
\v 16 Mosheh called (Nun’s son) Hoshea, ‘Yehoshua’ \add (Joshua)\add*. Those were the names of the men that Mosheh sent out to explore \add Kanaan\add*.
\p
\v 17 \add So\add* Mosheh sent them to explore Kanaan, telling them, “Go through the Negev and then up into the hill country.
\v 18 \add Find out\add* what the land’s like, and whether the people living there are \add militarily\add* strong or weak, and if they’re many or few.
\v 19 \add Find out\add* whether the land is good or bad, what cities they live in, and \add how fortified they are\add*.
\v 20 \add Find out\add* whether the soil is fertile or not, whether or not there’s trees there. \add Be courageous\add* and bring back some of the produce from that land.” (He said that because it was the time \add of the year\add* when \add grapes were starting to ripen\add*.)
\p
\v 21 \add So\add* \add the twelve men\add* went and explored the region from the Tsin wilderness \add in the south, all the way\add* up to Rehob at Levo-Hamat \add in the north\add*.
\v 22 \add They started\add* in the Negev, and went as far as Hevron where some of Anak’s descendents lived: Ahiman, Sheshay, Talmai. Hevron had been built seven years \add before\add* Tsoan in Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*.
\v 23 When they got to the Eshkol riverbed, they cut off a branch \add with\add* a cluster of grapes, and carried it on a pole between two of them, \add along with some\add* pomegranates and figs.
\v 24 (That place was then called Eshkol, \add meaning ‘cluster’\add*, because of the cluster \add of grapes\add* they’d taken from there.)
\s2 The reports from the scouts
\p
\v 25 Forty days \add later\add*, they returned from exploring that land
\v 26 and went to Kadesh in the Paran wilderness. There they reported back to Mosheh and Aharon and all the assembled people, and showed them the fruit from the land,
\v 27 and told \add them\add*, “We went to the land where you sent us, and it is indeed flowing with milk and honey, and this is its fruit.
\v 28 However, the people living in that land are powerful, and the cities are very well fortified. Also, some of the Anak people group live there.
\v 29 The Amalekite people live in the Negev, and the Hittites, Yebusites, and Amorites live in the hill country, and the Kanaanites live along the coast and \add along\add* the Yarden \add (Jordan) river\add*.”
\p
\v 30 Then Kalev \add (Caleb)\add* \add raised an arm\add* to quieten the people in front of Mosheh \add and stated\add*, “We’ll certainly go in there and take it over, because we’re capable of \add going\add* against \add them\add*.”
\p
\v 31 \add But\add* the men who’d gone in with him \add argued\add*, “\add No,\add*, we’re not able to \add battle\add* against them because \add they’re\add* stronger than us.”
\v 32 Then \add they went on to\add* bring out a bad report to the \add Israelis\add* about the land that they’d explored, saying, “The land that we passed to explore is a land that devours those who live in it. \add In addition,\add* all the people we saw in there were \add tall\add* \add and powerful\add*,
\v 33 plus we saw the Nefilim (descendants of Anak), and we felt \add as small as\add* grasshoppers \add compared to them\add*, and \add that’s how they saw us as well\add*.”\x + \xo 13:33: \xt Gen 6:4.\x*
\c 14
\s1 The people rebel
\p
\v 1 The assembled \add people\add* \add cried loudly that entire\add* night,
\v 2 and then they \add started\add* to protest against Mosheh and Aharon. They \add were all saying\add*, “If only we’d died in Egypt or \add back there\add* in this wilderness.
\v 3 Why did Yahweh bring us to this \add place only to be slaughtered in battle with our wives and children being taken as\add* plunder? Wouldn’t it be better for us to return to Egypt?”
\v 4 \add So they said to each other\add*, “Let’s \add choose a new leader\add* to take us back to Egypt.”
\p
\v 5 Then Mosheh and Aharon fell \add to their knees with their faces bowed in front of all the assembled Israelis\add*.
\v 6 Then Nun’s son Yehoshua and Yefunneh’s son Kalev, two of those who’d explored that land, tore their clothes \add in grief\add*
\v 7 and spoke to all \add those Israelis gathered there\add*, “The land that we passed throughout and explored is a very, very good \add place\add*.
\v 8 If Yahweh \add is pleased with\add* us, then he’ll take us into \add it\add* and give it to us—that land flowing with milk and honey.
\v 9 However, you all mustn’t rebel against Yahweh, and you mustn’t be scared of the people in that \add area\add* because they’ll \add be like\add* bread for us. \add There’s nothing left to protect them as\add* Yahweh is with us, \add so\add* don’t be afraid.”
\v 10 Then the \add mass of people talked about killing them by throwing rocks at them, but\add* Yahweh’s \add brilliant light\add* \add suddenly\add* appeared to all the \add Israelis from the sacred\add* tent.
\s1 Mosheh asks Yahweh to forgive
\p
\v 11 Yahweh said to Mosheh, “How long will this people group spurn me for? \add How long will they refuse to believe in me for\add*, \add despite all the miracles that I’ve done among them\add*?
\v 12 I’ll strike \add them\add* with a plague and destroy them. I’m make you into a nation that’s greater and more powerful than them.”
\p
\v 13 \add But\add* Mosheh \add disagreed with\add* Yahweh, “Then Egypt will hear about how you \add used\add* your power to bring \add these\add* people out from among them,
\v 14 and they’ll \add report\add* to the inhabitants of \add Kanaan\add*, because those \add inhabitants\add* have heard that \add you\add*, Yahweh, are \add right here\add* in the middle of \add us Israeli people\add*, and how your cloud rests on us, and how you lead \add us\add* with that pillar of cloud that becomes a pillar of fire at night.
\v 15 If you \add exterminate all the Israelis\add*, those nations who’ve heard about your fame will say,
\v 16 ‘\add That\add* Yahweh couldn’t take those people into the land that he promised them, so he slaughtered them in the wilderness.’
\v 17 \add So\add* may the power of my master be great, just as you’ve \add previously\add* said,
\v 18 ‘Yahweh is \add slow to anger\add* and \add quick to show\add* loyal commitment, \add forgiving disobedience and rebellion\add*. \add Yet he doesn’t leave the guilty\add* unpunished, \add bringing the consequences\add* of the father’s disobedience onto \add the next three generations\add*.’
\v 19 Please forgive \add this\add* people for their \add disobedience\add*, \add applying\add* your \add incredible\add* loyal commitment like how you did when you brought these people from Egypt all the way to here.”
\p
\v 20 “I’ve forgiven \add as per your request\add*,” Yahweh \add replied\add*,
\v 21 “\add however,\add* as surely as I live and as all the land is filled with Yahweh’s \add light\add*,
\v 22 \add and despite\add* \add them\add* all seeing my \add power\add* and the \add miracles\add* that I did \add both\add* in Egypt and in the wilderness, they’ve \add now\add* tested me \add many\add* times and \add haven’t done what I told them\add*,
\v 23 \add so there’s no way\add* that they’ll \add enter\add* the land that I promised to their ancestors. All those who despised me won’t \add get to\add* \add enter\add* it.
\v 24 \add However,\add* my servant Kalev \add (Caleb)\add* has a different spirit with him, and he wholeheartedly followed me, \add so\add* I’ll take him into the land \add that he explored\add*, and his descendants will inherit it.\x + \xo 14:24: \xt Josh 14:9-12.\x*
\v 25 The Amalekites and Kanaanites live in the valleys. Tomorrow, you all must turn and set off towards the wilderness via the \add route to\add* the Red Sea.
\s1 Punishment for the protestors
\p
\v 26 Then Yahweh said to Mosheh and Aharon,
\v 27 “\add How much longer\add* \add do I have to put up with\add* this evil gathering that grumble against me? I’ve heard the \add complaints that the Israelis are making\add* against me.
\v 28 Tell them \add this\add*, ‘Yahweh declares that as I live, \add your own words that I heard are exactly what\add* I’ll do to you all.
\v 29 \add Indeed\add* you’ll \add die there\add* in the wilderness—all those men who were listed as being twenty years old and older that complained against me.
\v 30 You all won’t enter that land that I \add would have\add* \add used my power\add* to settle you into. \add The only exceptions are\add* Yefunneh’s son Kalev \add (Caleb)\add* and Nun’s son Yehoshua \add (Joshua)\add*.
\v 31 The children of you all that you said would \add be taken\add* as plunder, I take \em them\em* in and they’ll \add experience\add* the land that you all have rejected,
\v 32 \add but your bodies will remain\add* in this wilderness.
\v 33 Your sons will become shepherds in the wilderness for forty years, and they will suffer for your unfaithfulness until you \add yourselves\add* all \add become\add* corpses in the wilderness.
\v 34 \add For each day\add* that you explored the land, you’ll all \add bear your disobedience for one year\add*, so forty days will be forty years \add of experiencing\add* my displeasure.
\v 35 I, Yahweh, have spoken that I’ll certainly do that to this evil community that joined together against me. They’ll meet their end and die there in the wilderness.’ ”
\p
\v 36 \add Now\add* those \add ten\add* men who Mosheh had sent in to explore the land, and who’d returned and the made the whole assembly grumble against him because of their evil report about the land,
\v 37 they died of a plague \add in front\add* of Yahweh after producing that evil report.
\v 38 \add However,\add* Yehoshua (\add Joshua\add*—Nun’s son) and Kalev (\add Caleb\add*—Yefunneh’s son) who had also explored that land, continue to live on.
\s1 The wrong-minded attempt to invade
\r (Deu. 1:41-46)
\p
\v 39 \add So\add* Mosheh \add passed on to the Israelis what Yahweh had said\add*, and the people \add were extremely sad\add*.
\v 40 Early the \add next\add* morning, they went up towards the hilltops, saying, “Look at us all here! \add Yes,\add* we sinned \add yesterday, but today\add* we’ll go up to the place that Yahweh said.”
\p
\v 41 “What’s that?” Mosheh \add responded\add*. “\add Don’t go against Yahweh’s instructions because\add* \add your plan\add* won’t succeed.
\v 42 Don’t \add continue onwards\add* because Yahweh \add isn’t with you\add* and \add for sure\add* you’ll all be defeated by your enemies
\v 43 because \add you’ll all be facing\add* the Amalekites and the Kanaanites and you’ll die by the sword. Yes, you’ve turned away from following Yahweh so \add he\add* won’t be with you all.”
\p
\v 44 \add Nevertheless,\add* they dared to \add continue\add* up to the tops of the hills, \add but\add* \add neither\add* Mosheh nor the box \add containing\add* the agreement with Yahweh, left the camp.
\v 45 Then the Amalekites and Kanaanites that lived in that \add part of the\add* hill country attacked them and \add killed\add* them as far down as Hormah.
\c 15
\s1 Instructions about sacrifices and offerings
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*,
\v 2 “Tell the \add Israelis\add* that when they \add enter the region that I’ll give them to live in\add*, \add they must do this:\add*
\v 3 \add When\add* you all make a gift to Yahweh—a burnt offering or a sacrifice, to fulfill a vow, or as a freewill offering, or at your appointed times, to make a scent of pleasing for Yahweh from the cattle or from the flock—
\v 4 then the \add donor\add* must present their offering to Yahweh, \add along with\add* a grain offering of a kilogram of fine flour mixed with 0.9 litres of \add olive\add* oil.
\v 5 \add Also\add* about a quarter of a litre of wine for the drink offering \add must be offered\add* with the burnt offering and/or with \add each\add* male lamb.
\v 6 For a ram, there must also be a grain offering of two kilograms of fine flour mixed with mixed with 1.2 litres of oil
\v 7 plus 1.2 litres of wine, all to be presented as a pleasing aroma to Yahweh.
\v 8 When you offer a young bull as a burnt offering or as a sacrifice such as fulfilling a vow or as a peace offering,
\v 9 the \add donor\add* must present a grain offering of 3.5kg of fine flour mixed with two litres of oil,
\v 10 plus a drink offering of two litres of wine, all to be presented as a pleasing aroma to Yahweh.
\p
\v 11 That’s what must be done for each bull or ram or lamb or young goat.
\v 12 Whatever number \add of animals\add* that you offer, \add there must be the appropriate\add* \add grain and wine offerings\add*.
\v 13 Every \add native-born\add* \add Israeli\add* must do that when presenting a gift, all to be presented as a pleasing aroma to Yahweh.
\p
\v 14 If a \add foreigner is staying with you all\add* or living among you for \add multiple\add* generations, and they make an offering to Yahweh with a pleasing aroma, then they must \add follow the same instructions\add* as all of you.
\v 15 \add Yes,\add* \add the same regulations apply to both you and the foreigners living among you all\add*. \add That will always apply—foreigners in front of Yahweh must do the same\add* as all of you.
\v 16 One \add set of\add* instructions and regulations for \add both\add* you and the foreigner that lives among you all.
\p
\v 17 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 18 “Tell the \add Israelis that\add* when you get to the land that I’m taking you to,
\v 19 and \add you all settle there and\add* start eating \add food that you’ve grown there\add*, you all must \add dedicate\add* a \add special\add* contribution to Yahweh.
\v 20 You must present the first portion of your dough and hold it up \add just\add* like a presentation from the threshing floor.
\v 21 You all must do that \add each year\add* with your first dough, even through \add future\add* generations.
\s1 Handling unintentional non-compliance
\p
\v 22 “\add However,\add* if you \add do something wrong\add* and don’t follow all these instructions that Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 23 i.e., \add don’t follow\add* everything that Yahweh has commanded through Mosheh from when the commands were given \add right\add* through to \add future\add* generations,
\v 24 then \add assuming that it was an accident\add*, the community must offer a young bull for a burnt offering to make a pleasing aroma for Yahweh, along with its grain offering and drink offering as per the instructions, plus a male goat as a sin offering.
\v 25 \add That way\add* the priest will make atonement for the \add Israeli community\add* and they’ll be forgiven because it was a mistake and they’d brought their gift as an offering to Yahweh plus their sin offering because of their mistake.
\v 26 The \add Israeli community\add* will be forgiven along with \add any foreigner living among them\add* because it accidentally affected the entire community.
\p
\v 27 “\add Now\add* if a single person disobeys by mistake, then that person must present a one-year-old female goat as a sin offering,
\v 28 and the priest will make atonement for that person. \add In that way,\add* the one making a mistake in front of Yahweh will be forgiven.
\v 29 \add Both\add* \add native-born Israelis\add* and foreigners living among them must \add all\add* \add follow the same instructions after\add* making a mistake.
\v 30 \add However,\add* any person who \add disobeys defiantly\add*, whether native-born or foreigner, they are slandering Yahweh and that person must be \add driven out of the community\add*
\v 31 because they’ve despised Yahweh’s message and disobeyed his instructions. That person must be \add completely\add* cut off and their guilt \add remains\add* on them.
\s1 Violating the rest day
\p
\v 32 \add One day\add* when the \add Israelis\add* were in the wilderness, they \add noticed\add* a man gathering firewood on the rest day,
\v 33 and those who \add caught\add* him took him to Mosheh and Aharon and the rest of the community.
\v 34 They put him into custody, because it hadn’t been decided what to do with him,
\v 35 and Yahweh told Mosheh, “That man must definitely be put to death—the community must do it outside the camp by throwing rocks at him.”
\v 36 \add So\add* the community took him outside the camp, and they executed him by throwing rocks at him just as Yahweh had commanded Mosheh.
\s1 Tassels on clothes
\p
\v 37 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 38 “Tell the \add Israelis that\add* they must make tassels on the corners of their \add outer\add* \add robes\add*. Each tassel must have a blue cord, and they must do this \add for all future\add* generations.
\v 39 Then when you see a tassel, it’ll remind you of Yahweh’s instructions, and \add so\add* you’ll \add follow\add* them \add rather than your own desires and lusts that lead you all into unfaithfulness\add*.
\v 40 \add Instead,\add* you’ll remember and follow my instructions, and \add stay pure\add* for your god.
\v 41 I am your god Yahweh—the one who brought you all out of Egypt (Heb. Mitsrayim) to be your god. I am Yahweh your god.”
\c 16
\s1 Korah’s rebellion
\p
\v 1 \add Now\add* Korah (son of Yitshar, son of Kehat, son of Levi) \add along with\add* Datan and Aviram (sons of Eliav) and On (son of Pelet)\x + \xo 16:1-35: \xt Jude 11.\x*
\v 2 \add rebelled\add* against Mosheh along with 250 \add respected, Israeli\add* community leaders.
\v 3 They \add got together and challenged\add* Mosheh and Aharon, “\add You think you’re great but the entire community is sacred and has Yahweh among us, so why do you consider yourselves more important than Yahweh’s community?\add*”
\p
\v 4 \add When\add* Mosheh heard \add that\add*, he fell \add to his knees with his face to the ground\add*
\v 5 and \add responded\add* to Korah and his \add supporters\add*, “\add Tomorrow\add* morning Yahweh will show who’s sacred and who belongs to him. \add Yahweh will present his chosen leader\add*. make known who is to him and the holy one, and he will present to him, and whom he chooses he will present to him.
\v 6 \add So\add* Korah and \add supporters\add*, bring incense burners
\v 7 and put \add burning coals\add* and incense in them, and bring them to \add Yahweh’s presence\add* tomorrow. Then the man that Yahweh chooses will be the sacred one. \add It’s you Levites who think you’re\add* great.”
\p
\v 8 Then Mosheh told Korah, “\add You Levites\add*, please listen.
\v 9 Isn’t it enough for you all that Yisrael’s god separated you from the \add rest of\add* the Israeli community to present you to him to serve in Yahweh’s residence and to stand in front of the gatherings to minister to them?
\v 10 \add Yahweh\add* has presented you and your brothers, the \add other\add* \add Levites\add* to approach \add him\add*. Are you all wanting the priesthood \add now\add* also?
\v 11 \add So\add* it’s Yahweh that you and your group are opposing, not \add really\add* Aharon that you’re all grumbling about.”
\p
\v 12 Then Mosheh \add summoned\add* Eliav’s sons Datan and Aviram \add but they refused\add*, “We won’t come.
\v 13 \add Isn’t it enough\add* that you brought us \em out\em* of a land flowing with milk and honey, to kill us \add here\add* in the wilderness, without also making yourself the ruler over us?
\v 14 \add What’s more\add*, you didn’t bring us into a land flowing with milk and honey or give us an inheritance of land and vineyards. Will you gouge out the eyes of those \add Kanaanites\add* \add so that we can defeat them\add*? \add No,\add* we won’t come.”
\p
\v 15 \add That made\add* Mosheh very angry and he told Yahweh, “Don’t \add accept\add* their grain offering. I’ve \add never\add* taken \add even\add* one donkey from them \add or done anything bad to any of\add* them.”
\p
\v 16 Then Mosheh told Korah, “You and all your group, \add must appear in front\add* of Yahweh tomorrow, \add as will\add* Aharon.
\v 17 \add Each\add* man must bring his pan with incense \add burning in it\add* and present it to Yahweh—\add all 250 of you as well as\add* Aharon.
\v 18 \add So\add* \add the next day,\add* they all brought their pans with \add burning coals\add* and incense in them, and they stood at the entrance of the \add sacred\add* tent, as did Mosheh and Aharon.
\v 19 plus Korah had \add also\add* assembled the entire community \add to oppose\add* \add Mosheh and Aharon\add* at the entrance to the \add sacred\add* tent. Then Yahweh’s \add brilliance\add* appeared to all the community
\v 20 and Yahweh warned Mosheh and Aharon,
\v 21 “Get away from \add all those people\add*, then I can destroy them in an instant.”
\p
\v 22 \add However,\add* \add Mosheh and Aharon\add* fell \add to their knees with their faces to the ground and interceded\add*, “God, \add you are\add* the god \add who gives life to everything\add*. Will you be angry at the entire community \add because of\add* the sin of one man?”
\v 23 \add So\add* Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 24 “Tell the \add people to keep back from the homes\add* of Korah, Datan, and Aviram.”
\p
\v 25 Then Mosheh \add walked to\add* \add the homes of\add* Datan and Aviram, and the \add Israeli\add* elders followed behind him,
\v 26 and he told the \add people\add*, “Please \add keep back\add* from the tents of these wicked men, and don’t touch anything of theirs, in case you get caught up in their \add disobedience\add*.”
\v 27 \add So\add* \add the rest of the Israelis\add* \add kept back\add* from the residences of Korah, Datan, and Aviram. \add Meanwhile,\add* Datan and Aviram had come out of their tents, and were standing at the entrances with their wives and children.
\p
\v 28 Then Mosheh said, “This is how \add you’ll all\add* known that \add it was\add* Yahweh \add who selected me for this role\add*—it’s \add never\add* \add been something that I aspired to\add*:
\v 29 If all these men \add die a natural death like most people\add*, then Yahweh didn’t \add choose\add* me,
\v 30 \add but\add* if Yahweh \add does something new\add* and the ground opens its mouth and swallows them and their homes and tents and \add all their possessions\add*, and if they then go down alive into \add their grave\add*, then you’ll all know that it was because these men rejected Yahweh.”
\p
\v 31 \add As soon as Mosheh had finished speaking\add*, the ground below \add those men\add* split open
\v 32 and the earth opened its mouth and swallowed them and their homes and every man who \add backed\add* Korah along with all \add their\add* property.
\v 33 They went down alive to \add their grave\add*, along with everything they owned, and then the ground covered over them and they \add vanished\add* from the \add community\add*.
\v 34 All the people who were around them fled \add away\add* \add screaming because they were afraid of getting swallowed by the earth as well\add*.
\p
\v 35 Then Yahweh \add sent\add* fire that consumed the 250 men who were presenting incense.
\s1 The incense burners
\p
\v 36 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 37 “Tell the priest Eleazar (Aharon’s son) to \add collect the incense pans\add* from \add those who were burnt\add*, and scatter the \add coals far away\add* because they’re sacred.
\v 38 The pans of those who \add rebelled at the expense of their own lives\add* must be hammered into thin plates \add to be attached\add* to the altar, because they presented them \add in front\add* of Yahweh and \add now\add* they’re sacred, and they’ll become a \add reminder\add* for the \add Israelis\add*.
\v 39 \add So\add* the priest Eleazar took the bronze incense burners that had been presented by those men who’d been burnt up, and they were hammered into a plating for the altar
\v 40 for a memorial for the \add Israelis\add* just as Yahweh had told him via Mosheh. That’s a reminder that no one who’s not a descendant of Aharon is allowed to approach Yahweh with incense burners, so they don’t end up like Korah and his \add supporters\add*.
\s1 The people complain and cause a plague
\p
\v 41 \add However,\add* the next day the \add Israelis\add* complained about Mosheh and Aharon, “\add It was you who\add* killed Yahweh’s people.”
\v 42 \add But\add* as the community gathered \add there\add* against Mosheh and Aharon, they \add looked across\add* to the \add sacred\add* tent, and wow, the cloud covered over it and Yahweh’s \add brilliance\add* appeared.
\v 43 Mosheh and Aharon went \add over\add* to the front of the \add sacred\add* tent,
\v 44 and Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 45 “Get away from this \add gathering\add* and then I’ll finish them \add in an instant\add*.”
\p \add But\add* \add Mosheh and Aharon\add* fell \add to their knees with their faces to the ground\add*,
\v 46 and Mosheh told Aharon, “Take the incense burner, and put fire in it from the altar and incense, and take it quickly to the \add people\add* and make atonement for them, because Yahweh’s rage is \add already\add* \add burning\add*—the plague has begun.”
\v 47 \add So\add* Aharon took it as Mosheh had told \add him\add* and ran into the middle of the \add people\add*. Wow, the plague had already begun, \add so he burnt\add* incense and made atonement for \add them\add*.
\v 48 He stood between those who were dying and those still alive, and the plague was restrained.
\v 49 There were 14,700 \add people\add* who died from the plague, in addition to those who’d died due to Korah’s \add rebellion\add*.
\v 50 Then Aharon returned to Mosheh at the \add sacred\add* tent entrance, \add as\add* the plague had been \add stopped\add*.
\c 17
\s1 The budding of Aharon’s rod
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 2 “Tell the \add Israelis\add* to bring you twelve staffs—one from each ancestral \add tribe\add* with the leader’s name inscribed on it,
\v 3 and inscribe Aharon’s name on the staff for the \add Levites\add* so there’s one for each tribe.
\v 4 Put them \add all\add* in the \add sacred\add* tent in front of the \add sacred box\add* where I meet with you,
\v 5 and then the staff of the man that I choose \add to be the priest\add* will sprout. Then the \add people\add* can stop complaining to me about you.”
\p
\v 6 \add So Mosheh passed the message on to the Israeli\add* leaders and they gave him one staff for each leader—\add a total of twelve including Aharon’s one\add*,
\v 7 and Mosheh \add laid\add* them \add in front\add* of Yahweh in the \add sacred\add* tent.
\p
\v 8 Then the next day when Mosheh went to the \add sacred\add* tent, wow, he saw that Aharon’s staff (\add representing\add* Levi tribe) had sprouted, plus it had blossomed and produced a flower and ripened almonds!\x + \xo 17:8-10: \xt Heb 9:4.\x*
\v 9 Mosheh took all the staffs \add out of the tent\add* to the people \add to look at\add* and \add each of the leaders\add* took back his own staff,
\v 10 then Yahweh told Mosheh, “Put Aharon’s staff \add back\add* \add in front of the sacred chest\add*. \add Keep it there as a reminder to\add* \add any\add* \add rebels to stop complaining against me so they won’t\add* die.”
\v 11 \add So\add* Moses did what Yahweh had commanded.
\p
\v 12 Then the \add Israelis\add* \add complained\add* to Mosheh, “Wow, \add we’re done for—it’s clear that we’re all going to die\add*!
\v 13 Everyone who goes close to Yahweh’s residence \add gets killed\add*. \add Won’t we all die\add*?”
\c 18
\s1 The work of priests and Levites
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Aharon \add (Aaron)\add*, “You and your \add Levite brothers and cousins\add* and \add all\add* your descendants must bear the \add imperfections\add* of the \add sacred tent\add*, and you and your sons must bear the \add imperfections\add* of your priesthood.
\v 2 Bring your \add Levite\add* brothers (your father’s tribe) to \add work closely with\add* you and to assist you \add as\add* you and your sons \add perform your duties at\add* the \add sacred\add* tent.
\v 3 They must look after the tent, however, they mustn’t approach the \add furnishings or utensils\add*, or the altar, so that both you and they won’t die.
\v 4 Then must \add work closely with\add* you and \add take care\add* of \add all the duties to do with\add* the \add sacred\add* tent, \add but\add* no \add outsider\add* \add is allowed to approach\add*.
\v 5 You \add priests\add* will \add take care\add* of the sacred place and the altar, and then there won’t be anymore fury against the \add Israeli people\add*.
\v 6 \add Now listen\add*, I’ve taken your brothers the Levites \add out from the rest of the Israelis\add* as a gift for you—they’re given to \add do the duties\add* at the \add sacred\add* tent.
\v 7 \add However,\add* it’s you and your sons who \add are the priests\add* who must serve for things to do with the altar and inside the curtain. Your priesthood is a gift of service, and any \add outsider\add* who approaches must be executed.”
\p
\v 8 Then Yahweh told Aharon, “\add Also listen\add*, I’ve put you in charge of \add looking after\add* the sacred offerings \add to me\add*. I’ve given them to you and your sons as your \add permanent income\add*.
\v 9 Every offering apart from the burnt offerings, will belong to you. That includes their grain offerings, their sin offerings, and their guilt offerings. \add Once they’re given, they become sacred,\add* and they’re for you and your sons.
\v 10 You and \add the males in your families\add* may eat that sacred offering \add but do remember that it’s sacred\add*.
\p
\v 11 “\add In addition,\add* the \add people’s\add* raised offerings belong to you, and they are \add permanently given to your entire families\add* to eat—everyone who’s ‘clean’ may eat them.
\p
\v 12 “All the best of the fresh oil, and the new wine and grain that they give to Yahweh, I give to you.
\v 13 The first \add portions of all their harvests\add* that they bring to Yahweh, belong to you—everyone in your \add families\add* who’s ‘clean’ may eat them.
\p
\v 14 “Everything throughout Yisrael that’s dedicated \add to Yahweh\add* will belong to you.\x + \xo 18:14: \xt Lev 27:28.\x*
\p
\v 15 “Every firstborn \add male\add* \add baby\add*, as well as animals, will belong to Yahweh, \add however\add* you must buy back the \add human babies\add* as well as the firstborns from the ‘unclean’ livestock.
\v 16 \add The babies\add* must be bought back when they’re one month old, paying five silver coins \add of the proper weight according to the scales at the sacred tent\add*.
\v 17 \add However,\add* the firstborn cows or sheep or goats can’t be bought back. They are sacred—you must sprinkle their blood on the altar and burn their fat as an offering that’s a soothing aroma for Yahweh.
\v 18 Their meat will belong to you, just like the breast or the right thigh of the wave offerings are yours.
\v 19 All sacred donations by the \add Israelis\add*, I’ve \add permanently\add* given to you and your \add children\add* to eat—it’s an \add irrevocable agreement with\add* Yahweh for you and your \add future\add* ancestors.”
\s1 The Levites’ share
\p
\v 20 Yahweh \add also\add* told Aharon, “You \add priests\add* won’t inherit \add any land or property\add*—I am your share and your inheritance \add among the Israelis\add*.
\p
\v 21 For an inheritance for the \add Levites\add*, I’ve given them all the tenths \add given by the Israelis\add* as their inheritance in exchange for their service at the \add sacred\add* tent.
\v 22 The \add other Israelis\add* mustn’t approach that tent \add or\add* they’ll \add incur guilt\add* and die,
\v 23 \add but\add* the Levites must serve at the \add sacred\add* tent and they must bear their \add inadequacies\add*. That order \add applies for all future generations\add*, \add including\add* the not inheriting any land \add like the other Israelis\add*.
\v 24 \add That’s\add* because I’ve given the Levites that tenth that the \add other Israelis\add* offer to Yahweh as a donation. That’s why I said that they won’t receive \add any other inheritance\add*.”
\s1 The Levites’ contribution
\p
\v 25 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 26 “Tell the Levites: ‘When you all receive the tenth from the \add Israelis\add* that I’ve given to you as you inheritance, then you must offer a tenth of that tenth as a donation to Yahweh.
\v 27 That will be considered as your contribution \add just\add* as if it was grain from the threshing floor, or \add juice\add* from the winepress.
\v 28 \add So\add* when you all offer that donation from all the tenths that you receive from the \add Israelis\add*, it must then be given as Yahweh’s contribution to the priest Aharon. DOUBLE-CHECK
\v 29 When an offering is presented to Yahweh, it must be \add the best parts of whatever is given\add*.’
\v 30 Also tell them, ‘When you all present \add the best of what was given\add*, it’ll be as \add it’s come straight\add* from the threshing floor or the winepress.
\v 31 \add The rest\add* is for your wages for the service you all do at the \add sacred\add* tent, and you all can eat it \add wherever you want to\add*.
\v 32 \add After donating the best tenth from it\add*, you won’t incur guilt for what you all do with the rest of it, \add however\add* you all mustn’t defile any sacred things or you’ll die.’ ”
\c 19
\s1 The red cow’s ashes
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh and Aharon,
\v 2 “This is \add a new\add* law that Yahweh has commanded, ‘Tell the \add Israelis\add* that they must bring you an unblemished red heifer \add with no defects\add* \add and that has never had a yoke on its neck\add*.
\v 3 Give it to the priest Eleazar, and he must take it outside the camp and have \add someone\add* slaughter it \add in front of him\add*.
\v 4 Then Eleazar must get some of its blood with his finger seven times and \add flick\add* it onto the ground \add directly in front\add* of the \add sacred\add* tent.
\v 5 Then \add while he watches\add*, they must \add completely\add* burn the heifer—its skin and flesh, and \add including\add* its blood and dung.
\v 6 \add Meanwhile,\add* the priest must take some cedar wood, hyssop, and scarlet wool, and throw them into \add the fire\add* where the cow is burning.
\v 7 Then the priest must wash his clothes and bathe. After that, he can return to the camp, \add but\add* \add he’ll\add* be ‘unclean’ until that evening.
\v 8 The \add man\add* who burnt \add the cow\add* must \add also\add* wash his clothes and bathe, and he will \add also\add* be ‘unclean’ until that evening.
\v 9 A ‘clean’ man must collect the cow’s ashes and place them in a \add sacred\add* place outside the camp where they can be used for water for purification for the \add Israelis\add* to purify from \add disobedience\add*.
\v 10 Then that man who collected the ashes must \add also\add* wash his clothes and be ‘unclean’ until that evening. Those regulations will permanently apply both to \add Israelis\add* and to foreigners living among them.
\s1 Contact with a corpse
\p
\v 11 “ ‘\add All those\add* who touch a dead, human body will be ‘unclean’ for seven days.
\v 12 On the third day, they must purify themselves, and then they’ll be ‘clean’ on the seventh day. (If they don’t purify themselves, they’ll won’t become ‘clean’ on that seventh day—
\v 13 if they’ve touched a dead, human body and don’t purify themselves, that would defile Yahweh’s residence, and \add so\add* they must be \add permanently removed from the camp\add*. If the purifying water wasn’t sprinkled on them, that ‘uncleanness’ will remain on them.)
\p
\v 14 “ ‘This is the regulation if a person dies in a tent: Everyone who was in the tent, and everyone that enters \add afterwards\add*, will all be ‘unclean’ for seven days,
\v 15 and every container that doesn’t have its lid on becomes ‘unclean’.
\v 16 \add Out in\add* the countryside, who touches the corpse of someone killed in a fight, or any dead human body or bone or grave, will be ‘unclean’ for seven days.
\v 17 \add Someone\add* must take some of the ashes from that burnt cow, and put them into a jar with some fresh, running water, then \add pour some of it over them\add*.
\v 18 Then a man who’s ‘clean’ must dip some hyssop in that water and sprinkle it onto the tent and all the containers \add in it\add* and everyone who lives in it or who touched the body or the bone or grave.
\v 19 On the third day, that ‘clean’ man must sprinkle \add that water\add* on the ‘unclean’ ones, and then must purify them on the seventh day. Then he \add himself\add* must wash his clothes and bathe, and will be ‘unclean’ until that evening.
\p
\v 20 “ ‘Anyone who’s ‘unclean’ and doesn’t purify themself, that person will be \add permanently removed from the camp\add* because they’ve made Yahweh’s sanctuary ‘unclean’. They didn’t sprinkle that purifying water on themself, so they \add remain\add* ‘unclean’.
\v 21 That will be a \add permanent\add* regulation. The person who’s had the purifying water sprinkled on them must wash their clothes, and any person who \add sprinkles\add* the water will be ‘unclean’ until that evening.
\v 22 Anything touched by an ‘unclean’ person becomes ‘unclean’, and anyone who touches an ‘unclean’ person will become ‘unclean’ until that evening.
\c 20
\s1 Water from the Kadesh rock
\r (Exo. 17:1-7)
\p
\v 1 Then in the first month \add of the next year\add*, all the \add Israelis\add* entered the Tsin \add (‘Thorny’ or ‘Thirsty’)\add* wilderness and the people \add camped\add* at Kadesh. \add While they were\add* there, Miryam died, and was buried there.
\p
\v 2 \add However,\add* there was no water \add to drink,\add* \add so the people\add* came against Mosheh and Aharon\x + \xo 20:2-13: \xt Exo 17:1-7.\x*
\v 3 and complained, “\add It would have been better if we’d died in front of Yahweh along with our relatives\add* \add back there\add*.
\v 4 Why did you two bring Yahweh’s people here to die in this wilderness, along with our livestock?
\v 5 Why did you bring us out of Egypt to bring us to this miserable place? There’s no \add grain\add* or figs, and no grapes or pomegranates. There’s \add not even\add* water to drink!”
\v 6 Then Mosheh and Aharon went from \add there\add* in front of the people to the entrance to the \add sacred\add* tent, where they fell \add to their knees with their faces to the ground\add*, and Yahweh’s brilliance appeared to them.
\p
\v 7 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 8 “Take \add Aharon’s\add* staff, then the two of you must command \add that\add* rock to \add pour out\add* water. Then water will come out of it, and both the people and the animals will \add have plenty to\add* drink.”
\p
\v 9 \add So\add* Mosheh took the staff from \add Yahweh’s residence\add* like he was told to.
\v 10 Then \add the two of them\add* gathered the people in front of the rock and told them, “Listen now \add you bunch of rebels\add*—do we have to bring water out of this rock for you?”
\v 11 Then Mosheh raised \add the staff\add* and hit the rock twice, and water \add gushed\add* out, and so the people and their animals were able to drink.
\p
\v 12 Then Yahweh \add scolded\add* Mosheh and Aharon, “Because you two \add publicly demonstrated that\add* you didn’t believe \add that what I say is absolute truth\add*, therefore you two won’t lead this community into the land that I’ve given them.”
\p
\v 13 \add That spring was named\add* ‘Merivah’ \add (meaning ‘Quarrelling’)\add* because that was where the \add Israelis\add* argued with Yahweh, and \add where he demonstrated his absolute truthfulness to\add* them.
\s1 Edom’s king refuses the Israelis’ passage
\p
\v 14 Then from there in Kadesh, Mosheh sent messengers to Edom’s king to \add ask\add* him, “This \add message is from\add* your \add Israeli relatives\add*. You \add are already aware\add* of all the hardship \add that we’ve been through\add*—
\v 15 \add how\add* our ancestors went down to Egypt and \add lived there for many years\add*, \add but then\add* the Egyptians \add mistreated\add* \add them\add*.
\v 16 \add However,\add* \add when\add* we cried out to Yahweh and he heard \add us\add* and sent a messenger and brought us out of Egypt, and now we’re in Kadesh town at the \add southern\add* border of your territory.
\v 17 \add Now\add* please let us pass through your \add country\add*. We won’t go through the countryside or the vineyards, and we won’t drink water from any well. We’ll stay on the king’s highway without turning to the right or the left, until after we’ve \add exited\add* at your \add northern\add* border.
\p
\v 18 \add But\add* Edom’s \add king\add* \add replied\add*, “You can’t pass through my country. \add If you do try to enter\add*, \add I’ll send my swordsmen out against you\add*.”
\p
\v 19 The \add Israelis reiterated\add*, “We’ll \add stay\add* on the highway, and if we or our livestock drink \add any of\add* your water, then we’ll \add pay what it’s worth so that’s no big deal\add*. \add Just let us walk\add* through.”
\p
\v 20 \add Again\add* \add the king\add* \add responded\add*, “You may not pass through.”
\p Then Edom \add sent a large, heavily-armed contingent to intimidate them\add*,
\v 21 and because they’d been refused passage through their territory, the \add Israelis\add* turned around \add and went via a longer, less direct route\add*.
\s1 Aharon’s death
\p
\v 22 \add So\add* the \add Israelis\add* left Kadesh and went to Mt. Hor.
\v 23 \add There\add* near the Edom border, Yahweh told Aharon and Mosheh,
\v 24 “Aharon will be \add taken to join his ancestors\add* because he won’t not enter the land that I have given to the \add Israelis\add*, because you two rebelled against \add what I said at\add* the Meribah \add rock that gave water\add*.
\v 25 Take Aharon and his son Eleazar and \add climb\add* up Mt. Hor \add together\add*,
\v 26 then remove \add his high priest’s uniform\add* and put it on his son Eleazar. \add After that,\add* Aharon will die there and go to join his ancestors.”
\p
\v 27 \add So\add* Mosheh \add followed Yahweh’s instructions\add* and \add the three of them\add* \add climbed\add* Mt. Hor as the \add people\add* watched.
\v 28 Then Mosheh removed Aharon’s \add uniform\add* and put it on his son Eleazar. Aharon died there at the top of the mountain, and then Mosheh and Eleazar went \add back\add* down.\x + \xo 20:28: \xt Exo 29:29; Num 33:38; Deu 10:6.\x*
\v 29 When the \add assembled people realised\add* that Aharon had died, all the \add Israelis\add* mourned for thirty days for him.
\c 21
\s1 The defeat of Canaanites
\p
\v 1 \add When\add* Kanaanite king of Arad who lived by the wilderness, heard that Yisrael was coming on the Atarim road, he \add attacked them\add* and captured \add some prisoners\add*.\x + \xo 21:1: \xt Num 33:40.\x*
\v 2 Then the \add Israelis promised\add* Yahweh, “If you help us defeat \add them\add*, then we’ll \add completely destroy their towns (instead of looting them) as a way of offering them to you\add*.”
\v 3 Yahweh listened to \add what they said\add* and \add enabled them to defeat\add* those Kanaanites, then they dedicated the towns \add to Yahweh\add* and destroyed them, and they named that area ‘Hormah’ \add (which means ‘Destruction’)\add*.
\p
\v 4 Then they \add all\add* left Mt. Hor by the road \add going towards the Red\add* Sea to go around Edom, \add but\add* the people became impatient on the way\x + \xo 21:4: \xt Deu 2:1.\x*
\v 5 and they started to grumble against God and against Mosheh, “Why did you two bring us \add out of\add* Egypt \add just\add* to die in the wilderness, because there’s no bread and no water, and our \add insides detest that tasteless\add* ‘stuff’?”\x + \xo 21:5-6: \xt 1Cor 10:9.\x*
\v 6 \add So\add* Yahweh sent \add poisonous\add* snakes into the people, and many \add Israelis\add* were bitten and died.
\p
\v 7 The people came to Mosheh and \add begged\add*, “We’ve \add done wrong\add* by speaking out against Yahweh and against you. Pray to Yahweh \add for us\add* to get him to take the snakes away.” \add So\add* Mosheh prayed on the peoples’ behalf,
\v 8 and Yahweh told \add him\add*, “Make \add a model of\add* a snake and put it \add up\add* on a pole, and \add so that anyone who gets\add* bitten, can see it and live.”
\v 9 \add So\add* Mosheh made a snake out of bronze and \add attached it\add* \add to the top\add* of a pole, and \add anyone who was bitten by a snake\add* would \add recover when\add* they looked towards the bronze snake.\x + \xo 21:9: \xt 2Ki 18:4; Yhn 3:14.\x*
\s1 Going around Edom via Moav
\p
\v 10 Then the \add Israelis\add* set off and camped at Ovot.
\v 11 \add When\add* they left Ovot, they camped at Iyey-Haavarim in the wilderness \add near\add* Moav’s eastern border.
\v 12 From there they set off and camped by the Zared riverbed,
\v 13 \add before moving on\add* and camping at \add the north side of\add* the Arnon \add river\add*, in the wilderness that extends from the Amorite border. (The Arnon is the border between Moav and the Amorites.
\v 14 That’s why it says in the book about Yahweh’s battles:
\q1 “Vahev in Sufah, and the riverbeds there, and the Arnon River
\q1
\v 15 and the sloping valleys there,
\q1 that extend to Ar \add village\add* along Moav’s border.”)
\p
\v 16 From there they went to the well at Be’er \add (which means ‘Well’)\add*, where Yahweh told Mosheh, “Gather the people, and I’ll give them water.”
\v 17 \add That’s where the Israelis\add* sang this song:
\q1 “\add Come on\add*, well,
\q1 sing for \add this well\add*.
\q1
\v 18 the well dug by the leaders,
\q1 the \add top citizens\add* dug it out.
\q1 with their sceptres and their staffs.”
\p From that wilderness, \add the people went on\add* to Mattanah,
\v 19 then through Nahaliel and on to Bamot
\v 20 and from \add there\add* to the valley in the Moav countryside \add where Mt. Pisgh rises above\add* the desert.
\s1 Kings Sihon and Og defeated
\r (Deu. 2:26–3:11)
\p
\v 21 Then Yisrael sent messengers to the Amorite King Sihon,
\v 22 “Let us pass through your \add country\add*. We won’t turn off into any field or vineyard. We won’t \add take\add* water from any well. We’ll \add stay on\add* the king’s \add highway\add* until we’ve \add exited at\add* your \add northern\add* border.”
\v 23 \add However\add* \add King\add* Sihon \add refused them permission\add*, then \add he\add* \add took his whole army\add* into the wilderness to meet Yisrael, and they attacked \add them\add* at Yahats \add village\add*.
\v 24 \add Nevertheless,\add* Yisrael defeated them \add in battle\add* and took possession of his land from the Arnon \add river\add* up as far as Yabok \add where the Ammonites’ border was well fortified\add*.
\v 25 \add So\add* Yisrael took those Amorite cities \add including\add* Heshbon and \add the surrounding villages\add*, and \add started\add* living in them.
\v 26 (Heshbon was where the Amorite King Sihon lived, as he’d \add previously\add* fought against the former king of Moav and \add captured\add* all his land down as far as the Arnon \add river\add*.
\v 27 That was why the \add poets\add* say,
\q1 “Come to Heshbon—let it be rebuilt.
\q1 Let \add King\add* Sihon’s city be established
\q1
\v 28 because fire went out from Heshbon,
\q1 flame from Sihon’s city.
\q1 It consumed Ar in Moav,
\q1 \add and\add* the citizens on Arnon’s hilltops.\x + \xo 21:28-29: \xt Jer 48:45-46.\x*
\q1
\v 29 Moav, you \add won’t end well\add*.
\q1 Kemosh’s people have perished.
\q1 He’s made his sons into fugitives,
\q1 and given his daughters over to captivity
\q1 by the Amorite King Sihon.
\q1
\v 30 We’ve \add overpowered\add* them.
\q1 Heshbon has perished as far as Divon
\q1 and shattered Nofah as far as Medeva.)
\p
\v 31 \add So the Israelis\add* lived in the Amorite \add region\add*
\v 32 and Mosheh sent \add some men\add* to spy out Yazer, and the captured \add its villages\add* and \add drove\add* the Amorites out from there.
\p
\v 33 Then they turned and went up the road \add towards\add* Bashan, \add but\add* Bashan’s King Og came out with his army to meet them, and \add attacked them at\add* Edrei.
\v 34 Yahweh said to Mosheh, “Don’t be afraid of him because I’ve given him and all his people and his land to you, and you’ll \add be able to\add* do to him what you did to the Amorite King Sihon who lived at Heshbon.”
\v 35 \add So\add* they \add overcame\add* \add King Og\add* and his sons and all his people until there were no remaining survivors, then they took possession of \add their\add* land.
\c 22
\s1 King Balak sends for Bileam
\p
\v 1 Then the \add Israelis\add* set off for the Moav plains, and they camped there across the river from Yeriho \add (Jericho)\add*.
\v 2 The \add Moabite King\add* Balak (Tsipor’s son), saw everything that Yisrael had done to the \add Amorites\add*,
\v 3 and when he \add realised\add* that the \add Israelis\add* were very numerous, the Moabite \add people\add* became sick with fear.
\v 4 and \add they\add* told the elders at Midyan, “Now \add all that lot\add* will \add devour\add* everything that’s around us, \add just\add* like a cow \add completely cleans out\add* a green field.”
\p \add Now\add* Tsipor’s son Balak was Moav’s king at that time,
\v 5 and he sent messengers to Beor’s son Bileam \add (Balaam)\add* at Petor (which was their tribal land near the \add Euphrates\add* river). He \add requested help\add*, saying, “Listen, \add there’s a population here\add* that came out from Egypt. Wow, they’ve covered the \add entire surface in this region\add* and they’re living \add opposite\add* me.\x + \xo 22:5: \xt Num 31:8; 2Pe 2:15-16; Jude 11.\x*
\v 6 \add So\add* now please \add come and\add* curse this people group for me because they are more numerous than us, \add then\add* perhaps I’ll be able to \add attack\add* them and drive them out of the \add area\add*, because I know that anyone you bless will be blessed, and those who you curse will be cursed.”
\p
\v 7 \add So\add* the elders from Moav and from Midyan departed \add carrying the fees for divination with them\add*, and they went to Bileam and \add passed\add* Balak’s words on to him.
\v 8 \add Bileam\add* told them, “Stay here tonight, and \add in the morning\add*, I’ll bring you back \add answer, depending on what\add* Yahweh tells me,” and \add so\add* the Moav leaders stayed \add there\add* with Bileam.
\p
\v 9 \add That night,\add* God came to Bileam and \add asked\add*, “Who are those men with you?”
\p
\v 10 “Tsipor’s son, King Balak from Moav sent me \add a message\add*,” Bileam \add replied\add*.
\v 11 “\add He said that\add* \add shockingly\add* a people group has come out of Egypt and has covered \add his region\add*. \add He wants me to\add* go \add and\add* curse them for \add him, so that he’ll be able to attack them and drive them out of that area\add*.”
\p
\v 12 Then God told Bileam, “Don’t go with them—you mustn’t curse \add those\add* people, because they’re blessed.”
\v 13 The next morning, Bileam \add went over\add* and told Balak’s \add messengers\add*, “Go \add back\add* to your \add place\add*, because Yahweh has refused to \add let\add* me go with you.”
\v 14 \add So\add* the Moav leaders \add stood up\add* and went back to \add King\add* Balak, and told \add him\add*, “Bileam refused to come with us.”
\p
\v 15 \add However,\add* Balak sent \add back\add* a \add larger group of leaders who were even more senior than the first ones\add*,
\v 16 and they went and told Bileam, “Tsipor’s son \add King\add* Balak says, ‘Please don’t \add refuse to come here\add*,
\v 17 because I’ll honour you highly and do anything that you tell me to. \add Just\add* please come and curse this population for me.’ ”
\p
\v 18 “\add Even\add* if Balak gave me a houseful of gold and sliver,” Bileam told Balak’s servant, “I \add still\add* couldn’t go \add against Yahweh’s instructions, even if it was just to do something\add* small.
\v 19 \add However,\add* please do stay here tonight, and \add I’ll find out if Yahweh might have anything else\add* to say to me.”
\p
\v 20 \add That\add* night, God came to Bileam and told him, “If those men have come to summon you, \add get ready\add* and go with them, \add except that you must only give the message that I’ll tell\add* you.”
\v 21 \add So\add* in the morning, Bileam \add got ready\add* and saddled his donkey, and went with the Moav leaders.
\s1 The donkey talks
\p
\v 22 \add However,\add* God \add got angry\add* because he’d gone, and Yahweh’s messenger \add stood in the middle of the road to block them\add*. \add As\add* \add Bileam\add* rode on his donkey, accompanied by his two servants,
\v 23 the donkey saw Yahweh’s messenger \add standing there holding a sword in the middle of the road\add* and turned off the road and went into a field. \add So\add* Bileam whacked the donkey and forced it back onto the road.
\v 24 Then Yahweh’s messenger moved to a place where the road was very narrow, with vineyard walls on each side of the road.
\v 25 \add When\add* the donkey saw Yahweh’s messenger, it \add squeezed\add* close by the wall, and \add in doing so\add*, \add squashed\add* Bileam’s foot against the wall, \add so\add* he whacked it again.
\v 26 Then Yahweh’s messenger went past again and stood in a narrow place on the road where there was no \add room\add* to \add get past on either side\add*.
\v 27 \add This time, when\add* the donkey saw the messenger, it lay down on the ground with Bileam sitting on top of it. Bileam \add got very angry\add* and whacked the donkey again with his staff.
\v 28 Then Yahweh \add enabled the donkey to speak, and it asked\add* Bileam, “What did I do to you that you beat me these three times?”
\p
\v 29 “Because \add you’ve been messing me around\add*!” Bileam \add shouted\add*. “If only \add I’d been carrying a sword, then I would have killed\add* you!”
\p
\v 30 “Aren’t I your donkey that you’ve ridden \add all your life\add*?” the donkey \add asked\add* Bileam. “Have I ever \add done anything like that to you before\add*?”
\p And he said, “No.”
\p
\v 31 Then Yahweh uncovered Bileam’s eyes and he saw Yahweh’s messenger standing \add in the middle of\add* the road with his sword in his hand, and \add Bileam\add* \add fell to his knees and kept bowing his face to the ground\add*.
\v 32 Yahweh’s angel \add asked\add* him, “\add Why did you strike you donkey those three times? Listen, I came personally to oppose you\add* because \add you’re choosing a very dangerous path as far as I’m concerned\add*.
\v 33 Your donkey saw me and \add avoided me\add* those three times—if it hadn’t I certainly would have killed you already, \add but I would have let the donkey live\add*.”
\p
\v 34 “\add Yes,\add* I’ve \add done wrong\add*,” Bileam said to Yahweh’s messenger, “because I didn’t know that you were \add waiting\add* for me \add there\add* on the road. \add But\add* now, if \add you don’t want me to continue\add*, I’ll return \add home again\add*.”
\p
\v 35 “\add Continue on\add* with those men,” Yahweh’s angel told Bileam, “\add but make sure that you only pass on the message that I give\add* you.” \add So\add* Bileam \add carried on\add* with Balak’s leaders.
\s1 Balak welcomes Bileam
\p
\v 36 \add When\add* \add King\add* Balak heard that Bileam was coming, he went out to meeting him at a city in Moav that was on his border beside the Arnon \add river\add*.
\v 37 \add He\add* \add asked\add* Bileam, “Didn’t I send \add an urgent message\add* to summon you? Why didn’t you come \add then\add*? \add Did you think I couldn’t pay you enough\add*?”
\p
\v 38 “Look, I’ve come \add now\add*,” Bileam \add answered\add* Balak, “\add but can I say whatever I want\add*? \add No,\add* \add I have to deliver\add* whatever message God \add gives me\add*.”
\v 39 \add So\add* then Bileam went to Kiryat-Hutsot with Balak,
\v 40 \add where\add* Balak sacrificed sheep and cattle, and \add gave\add* \add some of the meat\add* to Bileam and to the leaders who were with \add them\add*.
\v 41 \add The next\add* morning, Balak took Bileam uphill to Bamot-Baal, and from there \add they\add* could see the outskirts of the \add Israeli camp\add*.
\c 23
\s1 Bileam blesses Yisrael
\p
\v 1 Then Bileam said to \add King\add* Balak, “\add Get them to\add* build seven altars for me \add here\add*, and prepare me seven bulls and seven rams.”
\p
\v 2 \add So\add* Balak did what Bileam had \add instructed\add*, then \add the two of them\add* offered up a bull and a ram on \add each\add* altar.
\v 3 Then Bileam told Balak, “\add You stand here beside\add* your burnt offering, and I’ll \add move away\add*. Perhaps Yahweh will \add want\add* to meet me, and then I’ll \add tell you whatever\add* he shows me.” Then he went to a bare hilltop
\v 4 \add where\add* God met \add him\add*, and \add Bileam\add* told him, “I \add organised\add* seven altars and offered up a bull and a ram on \add each\add* altar.”
\p
\v 5 Then Yahweh \add gave Bileam a message\add* and told \add him\add*, “Go back to Balak and tell \add him\add* that.”
\v 6 \add So\add* he went back to \add Balak\add* \add who\add* was \add still\add* standing by his burnt offering \add along with\add* all of Moav’s officials.
\p
\v 7 \add So\add* \add Bileam\add* \add gave his pronouncement\add*,
\q1 “\add It’s\add* Balak has brought me \add here\add* from Aram.
\q1 Moav’s king \add summoned me\add* from the eastern mountains.
\q1 ‘Go curse Yakov \add (Jacob)\add* for me,
\q1 and go denounce Yisrael.’
\q1
\v 8 How can I curse those who God hasn’t cursed?
\q1 How can I denounce those who Yahweh hasn’t denounced?
\q1
\v 9 \add Yes,\add* I can see \add them\add* from the top of \add those\add* rocks.
\q1 I look at \add them\add* from the hills.
\q1 Look, a population that lives by itself.
\q1 It doesn’t count itself among the \add other\add* nations.
\q1
\v 10 Who can count the dust that Yakov \add leaves behind\add*?
\q1 \add Who can even\add* count a quarter of the \add Israelis\add*?
\q1 Let me die like \add those\add* honourable \add people\add*,
\q1 and let my end be like \add theirs\add*.”
\p
\v 11 \add But\add* Balak \add demanded from\add* Bileam, “What have you done to me? I brought you \add here\add* to curse my enemies, and \add blast it all\add*—you’ve actually blessed \add them\add*!”
\p
\v 12 “Shouldn’t I be careful to \add only\add* say \add what Yahweh tells me\add*?” Bileam \add answered back\add*.
\s1 Bileam’s second blessing
\p
\v 13 Then \add King\add* Balak told \add Bileam\add*, “Please come with me to another place \add that you’ll be able to see them from\add*. You won’t \add be able to\add* see all of \add them\add*, only the edge \add of that large group\add*, \add but\add* you’ll will curse \add Yisrael\add* for me from there.”
\v 14 \add So\add* he took \add Bileam\add* to a field at the top of \add Mt.\add* Pisgah, and he built seven altars and offered up a bull and a ram on \add each\add* altar.
\p
\v 15 Bileam said to \add the king\add*, “You stand here beside your burnt offering, while I \add go over there so\add* \add Yahweh\add* \add can meet me\add*.”
\p
\v 16 Then Yahweh met with Bileam and \add gave him a message\add* and told \add him\add*, “Go back to Balak, and \add give him that message\add*.”
\v 17 \add So\add* he \add returned\add* to him where he was standing with the leaders from Moav beside the altar, and Balak \add asked\add* him, “What did Yahweh say?”
\p
\v 18 Then \add Bileam\add* \add gave his speech\add*,
\q1 “\add Look here\add*, Balak, and listen.
\q1 \add Pay attention\add* to me, son of Tsipor.
\q1
\v 19 God doesn’t lie because he’s not a human being,
\q1 and he’s not a mortal who might change his mind.
\q1 Whatever he’s said, he’ll do it.
\q1 Anything he \add promised\add*, he’ll make it \add happen\add*.
\q1
\v 20 Listen, I’ve received \add a command\add* to bless.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* he’s \add decided to\add* bless and I can’t reverse it.
\p
\v 21 \add Yahweh\add* hasn’t \add considered\add* hardship for Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*,
\q1 and he hasn’t seen trouble for Yisrael \add (Israel)\add*.
\q1 His god Yahweh is with \add that people group\add*,
\q1 and the king’s shout is over him.
\q1
\v 22 God brought them out of Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*,
\q1 →\add giving them strength\add* like a wild bull’s horns.
\q1
\v 23 \add No,\add* there’s no spell against Yakov,
\q1 and no divination against Yisrael.
\q1 \add People\add* will talk about Yakov/Yisrael,
\q1 →\add saying look\add* what God has done.
\q1
\v 24 That population stands up like a lioness,
\q1 and like a lion, it lifts itself up.
\q1 It won’t lie down until it’s devour its prey
\q1 and drunk the blood of those it killed.”
\p
\v 25 Then \add King\add* Balak \add scolded\add* Bileam, “Even \add if you won’t\add* curse them, definitely don’t \em bless\em* them!”
\p
\v 26 “Didn’t I \add already\add* tell you,” Bileam answered Balak, “\add that I can only pronounce what Yahweh tells me to\add*.”
\s1 Bileam’s third prophecy
\p
\v 27 Then \add King\add* Balak told Bileam, “Come \add with me\add*. I’ll take you to another place. Perhaps it will \add pleased\add* God \add if\add* you curse \add them\add* for me from there.”
\v 28 \add So\add* Balak took \add him\add* to the top of \add Mt.\add* Peor \add that faces down\add* to the wilderness,
\v 29 and \add again\add* Bileam told \add him\add*, “Build seven altars and prepare seven bulls and seven rams for me \add here\add*.”
\v 30 \add So\add* Balak \add followed those instructions\add* and offered a bull and a ram on \add each\add* altar.
\c 24
\p
\v 1 \add By now,\add* Bileam \add had realised\add* that Yahweh wanted to bless \add the Israelis\add*, \add so\add* he didn’t \add use his usual divinations\add* \add but instead, he just looked towards\add* the wilderness.
\v 2 He \add looked up\add* and saw Yisrael \add in their tents laid out by tribe\add*. Then God’s spirit came onto him,
\v 3 and he \add made his pronouncement\add*,
\q1 “\add This is\add* the declaration of Bileam, son of Beor—
\q1 the utterance of a man whose eyes are open.
\q1
\v 4 The declaration of someone who heard God’s message,
\q1 someone who sees the all-powerful one’s vision,
\q1 who bows to the ground with his eyes \add wide open\add*.
\q1
\v 5 \add Yes\add* Yakov, your tents look good.
\q1 \add Yes\add* Yisrael, \add the places where you’re living\add*:
\q1
\v 6 They stretch out like a riverbed.
\q1 Like gardens beside a river.
\q1 Like \add palms\add* that Yahweh has planted,
\q1 Like cedar \add trees\add* beside the waters.
\q1
\v 7 Water will \add spill over the top of\add* his buckets,
\q1 and his \add descendants will flow out\add* like water.
\q1 \add Yisrael’s\add* king will be greater than \add King\add* Agag,
\q1 and his kingdom will become honoured.
\q1
\v 8 God is bringing him \add here\add* from Egypt
\q1 \add with power\add* like the horns of a wild bull.
\q1 He’ll \add devastate\add* those nations \add that oppose him\add*.
\q1 He’ll break their bones, and his arrows will pierce them.
\q1
\v 9 He crouched—lying down like a lion or a lioness.
\q1 Who will rouse him?
\q1 Those who bless, you will be blessed,
\q1 ^\add but\add* those who curse you, will be cursed.\x + \xo 24:9: a \xt Gen 49:9; \xo b \xt Gen 12:3.\x*
\p
\v 10 Then \add King\add* Balak \add got very angry\add* with Bileam, and he banged his hands together and said \add angrily\add*, “I called you to \em curse\em* my enemies, and \add blast you\add*, you’ve actually blessed \add them\add* three times \add now\add*!
\v 11 \add Now get back to where you came from\add*! I said that I’d honour you \add very well\add*, but man, Yahweh has kept you from any honour!”
\p
\v 12 \add But\add* Bileam \add replied\add*, “Didn’t I also tell the messengers that you sent to me that
\v 13 even if you gave me a house full of gold and silver, I wouldn’t be able \add to say anything other than what Yahweh tells me\add*—whether good or evil? Whatever Yahweh tells me, that’s what I have to say.
\v 14 \add So yes,\add* I’ll go back home now, \add but first, allow me\add* to tell you what that people group will do to your people in the future.”
\p
\v 15 Then Bileam gave this pronouncement to Balak,
\q1 “\add This is\add* the declaration of Bileam, son of Beor—
\q1 the utterance of a man whose eyes are open.
\q1
\v 16 The statement from someone who hears God’s messages,
\q1 and the one who receives knowledge from the highest one,
\q1 who sees visions from the powerful one.
\q1 The one who falls to his knees with his eyes opened.
\q1
\v 17 I see him, \add but\add* not now.
\q1 I’ll look at him, \add but\add* he’s not close.
\q1 A star has marched out from Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*,
\q1 and a staff has risen from Yisrael \add (Israel)\add*.
\q1 He will crush Moav’s corners,
\q1 and destroy all of Shet’s \add (Seth’s)\add* descendants.
\q1
\v 18 Edom will become \add their\add* possession,
\q1 \add as will\add* his enemy, Seir.
\q1 Yisrael \add will project\add* strength.
\q1
\v 19 A ruler \add will come\add* from Yakov,
\q1 →and destroy the city’s survivors.”
\p
\v 20 Then \add Bileam\add* \add looked towards\add* Amalek and \add made this pronouncement\add*,
\q1 “Amalek is the first of the nations,
\q2 ^\add but\add* its end will be destruction.”
\p
\v 21 Then he \add looked towards\add* the Kenites and \add made this pronouncement\add*,
\q1 “Your dwelling is permanent,
\q1 and your nest is set in the cliffs.
\q1
\v 22 but you Kenites will be destroyed
\q1 when Ashhur \add (the Assyrians)\add* take you captive.”
\p
\v 23 Then \add finally,\add* \add Bileam\add* \add made this pronouncement\add*,
\q1 “Oh dear, who can \add survive\add* when God does \add all\add* that?
\q1
\v 24 Ships will come from the Kittim coast \add (Cyprus)\add*,
\q1 and they’ll \add damage\add* Asshur and Ever,
\q1 \add but they themselves\add* will be destroyed as well.”
\p
\v 25 Then Bileam \add packed up\add* and went home, and \add King\add* Balak also went on his way.
\c 25
\s1 Yisrael worships Baal at Peor
\p
\v 1 \add Meanwhile,\add* \add the Israelis settled down\add* at Shittim, and \add their men started sleeping with women from Moav\add*
\v 2 \add who then\add* invited them to sacrifices to their \add idols\add*. \add So\add* \add the Israelis\add* bowed down \add to the idols\add* and ate \add at the feasts\add*,
\v 3 and \add when\add* Yisrael consecrated themselves to Baal-Peor, Yahweh’s anger burned towards \add them\add*.
\v 4 Then Yahweh told Mosheh, “\add Execute\add* all the people’s leaders and \add display their bodies in broad daylight\add*, and then Yahweh’s \add anger\add* might turn back away from Yisrael.”
\p
\v 5 \add So\add* Mosheh to Yisrael’s judges, “\add Each of you must execute your men who have joined others to serve\add* Baal-Peor.”
\p
\v 6 \add Just then, unbelievably,\add* an \add Israeli\add* man \add came past\add* Mosheh and \add all the people\add* who were \add there outside\add* the \add sacred\add* tent weeping, and he was bringing a Midyanite woman \add with him\add*.
\v 7 \add When\add* Pinehas (son of Eleazar, son of Aharon) saw \add that\add*, he \add came out\add* from among the \add gathered people\add*, grabbed a spear,
\v 8 and followed the \add Israeli\add* man into \add his\add* tent. He \add plunged\add* the spear through the two of them—right through the man and the woman’s belly, and \add thus\add*, stopped the plague \add that had started\add* against the \add Israelis\add*.
\v 9 \add However,\add*, twenty-four thousand people had \add already\add* died from the plague.
\p
\v 10 Then Yahweh spoke to Mosheh,
\v 11 “Aharon’s grandson Pinehas has \add deflected my anger\add* from the \add Israelis\add* by \add demonstrating my seriousness about their behaviour\add*, \add so now\add* in my zeal, I won’t \add eliminate the Israelis\add*.
\v 12 \add So\add* tell him that I’m \add making\add* a peace agreement with him.
\v 13 It’s an agreement that gives him and his \add descendants\add* \add the rights to be priests\add* because he was zealous \add on his god’s behalf\add* and he \add worked towards removing the guilt\add* of the \add people\add*.”
\p
\v 14 The \add Israeli\add* man \add who was killed\add* with the Midyanite woman was Salu’s son Zimri, a \add clan leader\add* from the Shimeon tribe.
\v 15 The Midyanite woman \add who was killed\add* was Kozbi, the daughter of Tsur, a Midyanite clan leader.
\p
\v 16 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 17 “\add Attack\add* the Midyanites and \add destroy\add* them
\v 18 because they were \add treacherously deceiving\add* you all over the matter of Peor and Kozbi, the daughter of one of their leaders who was killed on the day of the plague at \add Mt.\add* Peor.”
\c 26
\s1 The second census
\p
\v 1 After \add the incident of\add* the plague, Yahweh told Mosheh and Aharon’s son Eleazar the priest,\x + \xo 26:1-51: \xt Num 1:1-46.\x*
\v 2 “\add Count all the Israeli people\add* \add again\add* \add listing all those by their clans\add* who’re twenty and over, and \add capable of going out to battle\add* for Yisrael.”
\v 3 \add So\add* there in the Moav plains, across the Yarden river opposite Yeriho \add (Jericho)\add*, Mosheh and the priest Eleazar \add gave these instructions\add* to \add the people\add*,
\v 4 “Yahweh has ordered \add us\add* \add to list\add* the names of the \add men\add* who came out from Egypt who’re twenty years old or older.
\s1 Reuven’s descendants
\v 5 Reuven was Yisrael’s eldest son, and his descendants came via his sons Hanok, Pallu,
\v 6 Hetsron, and Karmi.
\v 7 Those clans added up to 43,730 men.
\v 8 Pallu’s son was Eliav,
\v 9 and Eliav’s son were Nemuel, Datan, and Aviram. (That was the Datan and Aviram who were the leaders that rebelled\x + \xo 26:9 \xt 16:1-33.\x* against Mosheh and Aharon when they joined Korah’s rebellion against Yahweh.
\v 10 Then the earth \add split open\add* and swallowed them and Korah. Yahweh had also sent a fire that consumed 250 men, and they became a warning sign.
\v 11 \add However,\add* Korah’s descendants hadn’t died \add then\add*.)
\s1 Shimeon’s descendants
\p
\v 12 Shimeon’s descendants came via his sons Nemuel, Yamin, Yakin,
\v 13 Zerah, and Shaul.
\v 14 Those clans added up to 22,200 men.
\s1 Gad’s descendants
\p
\v 15 Gad’s descendants came via his sons Tsefon, Haggit, Shuni,
\v 16 Ozni, Eir,
\v 17 Arod, and Areli.
\v 18 Those clans added up to 40,500 men.
\s1 Yehudah’s descendants
\p
\v 19 Yehudah \add (Judah)\add* had two sons Er and Onan who died \add childless\add* in Kenaan.
\v 20 \add His\add* descendants came via his \add other\add* sons Shelah, Perets, and Zerah.
\v 21 Perets’s descendants \add came via his sons\add* Hetsron and Hamul.
\v 22 Those clans added up to 76,500 men.
\s1 Yissakar’s descendants
\p
\v 23 Yissakar’s \add (Issachar’s)\add* descendants came via his sons Tola, Puah,
\v 24 Yashuv, and Shimron.
\v 25 Those clans added up to 64,300 men.
\s1 Zevulun’s descendants
\p
\v 26 Zevulun’s descendants came via his sons Sered, Eylon, and Yahle’el.
\v 27 Those clans added up to 60,500 men.
\s1 Menashsheh’s descendants
\p
\v 28 Yosef’s \add (Joseph’s)\add* descendants came via his sons Menashsheh \add (Manasseh)\add* and Efrayim.
\v 29 Menashsheh’s descendants came from his son Makir and then his son Gilead.
\v 30 Gilead’s descendants came via his sons Iezer, Helek,
\v 31 Asriel, Shekem,
\v 32 Shemida, and Hefer.
\v 33 Hefer’s son Tselofehad had no sons—only daughters named Mahlah, Noah, Hoglah, Milkah, and Tirtsah.
\v 34 Those clans added up to 52,700 men.
\s1 Efrayim’s descendants
\p
\v 35 Efrayim’s descendants came via his sons Shutelah, Beker, and Tahan,
\v 36 Shutelah’s descendants came via his son Eran.
\v 37 Those clans added up to 32,500 men. These last two totals were \add all\add* Yosef’s \add (Joseph’s)\add* descendants.
\s1 Benyamin’s descendants
\p
\v 38 Benyamin’s descendants came via his sons Bela, Ashbel, Ahiram,
\v 39 Shefufam, and Hufam.
\v 40 Bela’s descendants came via his sons Ard and Naaman.
\v 41 Those clans added up to 45,600 men.
\s1 Dan’s descendants
\p
\v 42 Dan’s descendants came via his son Shuham.
\v 43 That clan had 64,400 men.
\s1 Asher’s descendants
\p
\v 44 Asher’s descendants came via his sons Yimnah, Yishvi, and Beriah.
\v 45 Beriah’s descendants came via his sons Hever and Malkiel.
\v 46 Asher’s daughter was named Serah.
\v 47 Those clans added up to 53,400 men.
\s1 Naftali’s descendants
\p
\v 48 Naftali’s descendants came via his sons Yahtse’el, Guni,
\v 49 Yetser, and Shillem.
\v 50 Those clans added up to 45,400 men.
\s1 The census total and the division of land
\p
\v 51 The total of all those tribes counted came to 601,730 men.\f + \fr 26:51 \ft Slightly smaller than the total of 603,550 from the first census, see \xt 1:46.\f*
\p
\v 52 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,\x + \xo 26:52-56: \xt Num 34:13; Josh 14:1-2.\x*
\v 53 “The land should be allocated to those \add clans\add* according to the number of their names, to become their inheritance.
\v 54 Those with larger numbers should receive more, and the smaller groups receive less, \add i.e.,\add* each inheritance \add depends on the number of family members\add*.
\v 55 \add You must throw\add* lots to determine \add which clan gets which piece of land\add*. \add The lands of the clans must be within their tribal lands\add*.
\v 56 \add Then the size of the area that will become\add* their inheritance must be apportioned according to the \add census numbers\add*.
\s1 Levi’s descendants
\p
\v 57 The listed Levites included the clans \add from Levi’s sons\add* Gershon, Kohat, and Merari,
\v 58 which were the Livnites, the Hevronites, the Mahlites, the Mushites, and the Korahites. \add Also,\add* Korah fathered Amram
\v 59 \add whose\add* wife was Levi’s daughter Yokeved who’d been born in Egypt. \add They\add* had two sons Aharon \add (Aaron)\add* and Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*, and their \add older\add* sister Miryam \add (Miriam)\add*.
\v 60 Aharon’s \add sons were\add* Nadav, Avihu, Eleazar, and Itamar,\x + \xo 26:60: \xt Num 3:2.\x*
\v 61 \add but\add* Nadav and Avihu had died when they’d offered Yahweh \add fire in a disobedient manner\add*.\x + \xo 26:61: \xt Lev 10:1-2; Num 3:4.\x*
\v 62 The male \add Levites\add* who were a month old or older came to 23,000, but they weren’t \add included in the above nation-wide count\add* because they \add didn’t inherit land in the same way as other tribes\add*.
\s1 Census summary
\p
\v 63 Those were the \add census results from when\add* Mosheh and the priest Eleazar counted the \add Israelis\add* on the Moav plains \add on the east side of\add* the Yarden river opposite Yeriho \add (Jericho)\add*.
\v 64 \add None of the men on those lists were on the previous lists done\add* by Mosheh and the priest Aharon when they’d counted the \add Israelis\add* in the Sinai wilderness,
\v 65 because Yahweh had told them that they’d certainly die \add there\add* in the wilderness until none of \add those alive\add* were left other than Yefunneh’s son Kalev \add (Caleb)\add* and Nun’s son Yehoshua \add (Joshua)\add*.
\c 27
\s1 Inheritances without sons
\p
\v 1 Then the daughters of Tselofehad (son of Hefer, son of Gilead, son of Makir, son of Menashsheh) approached. \add Their\add* names were Mahlah, Noah, Hoglah, Milkah, and Tirtsah.
\v 2 They stood \add in front of\add* Mosheh and the priest Eleazar and all the leaders and the people \add there\add* at the entrance to the \add sacred\add* tent, \add and\add* \add asked\add*,
\v 3 “Our father died in the wilderness, \add although\add* he wasn’t \add part of the group who joined Korah to rebel\add* against Yahweh—it was \add for his own personal disobedience\add* that he died. He didn’t have any sons
\v 4 \add but\add* why should his family name disappear from our clan \add just\add* because he had no sons? \add So\add* give us \add some land like\add* our father’s relatives will be getting.”
\p
\v 5 \add So\add* Mosheh took their case to Yahweh
\v 6 and \add he\add* \add responded\add*,
\v 7 “It’s right what Tselofehad’s daughters are saying. You must give them \add some land like their father’s relatives will be getting\add*. \add Give them whatever would have been given to their father as his\add* inheritance.
\v 8 \add Also,\add* tell the \add people\add* that if a man dies \add without sons\add*, then his inheritance should go to his daughter(s).
\v 9 If he had no \add children\add*, then \add it should go\add* to his brothers,
\v 10 and if he has no brothers, then \add it should go\add* to his father’s brothers.
\v 11 \add However,\add* if his father had no brothers, then the inheritance \add should go to his nearest blood-relative to become his possession\add*. That will \add become a permanent regulation\add* for Yisrael, just as Yahweh has commanded.”
\s1 Yehoshua succeeds Mosheh
\r (Deu. 31:1-8)
\p
\v 12 Then Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*, “Go up Mt. Avarim and look at the land that I’ve given to the \add Israelis\add*,\x + \xo 27:12-14: \xt Deu 3:23-27; 32:48-52.\x*
\v 13 and then you’ll \add die and join your ancestors\add* just like your brother Aharon \add did\add*.
\v 14 \add That’s because back\add* in the Tsin wilderness when the \add people complained about water\add*, you two rebelled against my \add command and failed to respect my holiness\add* in front of them. That was \add when you struck the rock\add* at Meribah \add near\add* Kadesh in the Tsin wilderness.”
\p
\v 15 Then Mosheh \add requested\add* Yahweh,
\v 16 “Yahweh, \add you\add* \add are the god who directs the spirits of all humankind\add*, \add so please\add* appoint a \add new leader for the Israeli people\add*
\v 17 who will \add stand in front of\add* them and lead them out and bring them in \add so\add* \add they\add* won’t be like sheep without a shepherd.\x + \xo 27:17: \xt 1Ki 22:17; Eze 34:5; Mat 9:36; Mrk 6:34.\x*
\p
\v 18 Then Yahweh told Mosheh, “Get Nun’s son Yehoshua \add (Joshua)\add*, a man who has \add my\add* spirit in him, and place your hands on him \add to indicate the transfer of leadership\add*.\x + \xo 27:18: \xt Exo 24:13.\x*
\v 19 Stand him in front of the priest Eleazar and all the assembly, and \add commission him as they watch\add*.
\v 20 Give him some of your authority so that all the \add Israeli\add* people can hear \add it\add*.
\v 21 \add When\add* \add he needs guidance\add*, he must stand \add in front\add* of the priest Eleazar and ask for Yahweh’s decision \add to be given via\add* the Urim. Then \add Yehoshua\add* and all the \add people\add* will go in or come out as per \add Yahweh’s\add* \add instructions\add*.”\x + \xo 27:21: \xt Exo 28:30; 1Sam 14:41; 28:6.\x*
\v 22 \add So\add* Mosheh did what Yahweh had ordered him to, and he \add presented\add* Yehoshua to the priest Eleazar and to the entire community.
\v 23 \add Mosheh\add* placed his hands on \add Yehoshua\add* and \add commissioned\add* him, just has Yahweh had said \add he\add* should.
\c 28
\s1 The daily offerings
\r (Exo. 29:38-46)
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*,
\v 2 “Give the \add Israelis\add* \add these instructions\add*: Ensure that you present to me the offerings \add and\add* food for offerings to be burnt at the \add proper\add* time.
\v 3 For the \add daily\add* burnt offering, present two one-year-old, male lambs that have no defects.
\v 4 One of those lambs must be offered in the morning, and the other in \add late afternoon\add*,
\v 5 \add each offered\add* along with a kilogram of fine flour mixed with a litre of \add olive\add* oil.
\v 6 That’s the regular burnt offering done like the first one at Mt. Sinai—the soothing aroma from the fire will be pleasing to Yahweh.
\v 7 The drink offering must \add also\add* be one litre for each lamb. That strong drink must be poured out in the sacred area as an offering to Yahweh.
\v 8 \add At the end of the afternoon,\add* offer the second lamb with the same-sized offerings of flour and wine as in the morning. \add When they’re burnt,\add* the aroma will be pleasing to Yahweh.
\s1 The Rest Day offerings
\p
\v 9 “On the Rest Day, \add it must be\add* two one-year-old, male lambs with no defects, along with 2 kilograms of fine flour mixed with oil, as well as the drink offering.
\v 10 That will be burnt every Rest Day, in addition to the regular \add daily\add* burnt offering and its drink offering.
\s1 The new month offerings
\p
\v 11 “\add On the first day of each month\add*, you all must bring Yahweh a burnt offering of two young bulls, one ram, and seven one-year-old, male lambs with no defects.
\v 12 Each bull must be offered with three kilograms of fine flour mixed with oil, each ram with two kilograms,
\v 13 and each lamb with one kilogram. \add All of that\add* will be a burnt offering with an aroma that will be pleasing to Yahweh.
\v 14 Their \add respective\add* drink offerings will be two litres of wine with the bull, 1.3 litres with the ram, and one litre with each lamb. That will be the burnt offering \add for the start of each new\add* month throughout the year.
\v 15 In addition to those burnt offerings and drink offerings, a male goat must \add also\add* be presented to Yahweh as a sin offering.
\s1 The ‘pass-over’ offerings
\r (Lev. 23:5-14)
\p
\v 16 “Yahweh’s ‘passover’ \add ceremony will start\add* on the 14th of the first month \add (Nisan = March/April) each year\add*.\x + \xo 28:16: \xt Exo 12:1-13; Deu 16:1-2.\x*
\v 17 The 15th will be \add the start of\add* the celebration—\add all your bread must be made without any rising agent\add*.\x + \xo 28:17-25: \xt Exo 12:14-20; 23:15; 34:18; Deu 16:3-8.\x*
\v 18 That first day, there’s to be a sacred assembly. No \add regular\add* work may be done that day.
\v 19 You all must offer two \add young\add* bulls, one ram, and seven one-year-old lambs with no defects to be burnt on the fire.
\v 20 Their \add associated\add* grain offerings must be three kilograms of fine flour mixed with \add olive\add* for the bull, two kilograms for the ram,
\v 21 \add and\add* one kilogram for each of the seven lambs.
\v 22 \add Also,\add* bring one male goat as a sin offering to make \add yourselves right with God\add*.
\v 23 Those offerings must be \em in addition\em* to the regular morning offerings
\v 24 \add and\add* must be offered for each of the seven days. The aroma of those burnt offerings will be pleasing to Yahweh, along with the regular burnt offering and its drink offering.
\v 25 On the seventh day, there’s to be \add another\add* sacred assembly. No \add regular\add* work may be done that day.
\s1 Harvest festival offerings
\r (Lev. 23:15-22)
\p
\v 26 “On the firstfruits day of the harvest festival, when you all present an offering of fresh grain to Yahweh, there’s to be a sacred assembly. No \add regular\add* work may be done that day.\x + \xo 28:26-31: \xt Exo 23:16; 34:22; Deu 16:9-12.\x*
\v 27 You all must present a burnt offering that’s a pleasing aroma for Yahweh, \add presenting\add* two \add young\add* bulls, one ram, and seven one-year-old male lambs.
\v 28 Their \add associated\add* grain offerings will be three kilograms of fine flour mixed with \add olive\add* oil for each bull, two kilograms for the ram,
\v 29 and one kilogram for each of the lambs.
\v 30 \add Also\add* for your sins, sacrifice one male goat to make \add yourselves right with God\add*.
\v 31 Those offerings along with their drink offerings must be offered in addition to the regular burnt offering and drink offerings. Ensure that they have no defects.
\c 29
\s1 The trumpeting celebration
\r (Lev. 23:23-25)
\p
\v 1 “On the first day of the seventh month \add (Tishrei = September/October) each year\add*, there’s to be a sacred assembly. No \add regular\add* work may be done that day—it’ll be a day of blowing horns.
\v 2 You all must present a \add young\add* bull, a ram, and seven one-year-old lambs, \add all\add* with no defects as a burnt offering to be a pleasing aroma for Yahweh.
\v 3 Their \add associated\add* grain offering will be three kilograms of fine flour mixed with \add olive\add* oil with the bull, two kilograms with the ram,
\v 4 and one kilogram for each of the seven lambs.
\v 5 \add Also\add* for your sins, sacrifice one male goat to make \add yourselves right with God\add*.
\v 6 Those are in addition to the monthly and regular \add daily\add* burnt offerings with their \add associated\add* grain offerings and drink offerings. The aroma of those burnt offerings will be pleasing to Yahweh.
\s1 The sacrifice for forgiveness
\r (Lev. 23:26-32)
\p
\v 7 “Each year on the 10th of this seventh month \add (Tishrei = September/October)\add*, there’s to be a sacred assembly. \add Don’t eat any food or do any regular work on that day\add*.\x + \xo 29:7-11: \xt Lev 16:29-34.\x*
\v 8 You all must present a \add young\add* bull, a ram, and seven one-year-old male lambs as a burnt offering that will be a pleasing aroma for Yahweh. Ensure that they have no defects.
\v 9 Their \add associated\add* grain offerings will be three kilograms of fine flour mixed with \add olive\add* oil for the bull, two kilograms for the ram,
\v 10 and one kilogram for each of the seven lambs.
\v 11 \add Also\add* for your sins, sacrifice one male goat, in addition to the one to make \add yourselves right with God\add* and the regular burnt offerings with their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings.
\s1 Offerings during the celebration in shelters
\r (Lev. 23:33-44)
\p
\v 12 “On the 15th of that seventh month, there’s to be \add another\add* sacred assembly. No \add regular\add* work may be done that day \add which will begin\add* seven days of celebration.\x + \xo 29:12-38: \xt Lev 23:34; Deu 16:13-15.\x*
\v 13 “You all must present thirteen \add young\add* bulls, two rams, fourteen one-year-old male lambs as a burnt offering that will be a pleasing aroma for Yahweh. Ensure that they have no defects.
\v 14 Their \add associated\add* grain offerings will be three kilograms of fine flour mixed with \add olive\add* oil for each bull, two kilograms for each ram,
\v 15 and one kilogram for each of the seven lambs.
\v 16 \add Also\add* for your sins, sacrifice one male goat to make \add yourselves right with God\add*, in addition to the regular burnt offerings with their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings.
\p
\v 17 “On the second day, you all must offer twelve \add young\add* bulls, two rams, fourteen one-year-old male lambs without defects,
\v 18 and their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings \add as already stipulated\add*.
\v 19 \add Also\add* for your sins, sacrifice one male goat to make \add yourselves right with God\add*, in addition to the regular burnt offerings with their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings.
\p
\v 20 “On the third day, \add the sacrifice will be\add* eleven young bulls, two rams, fourteen year-old male lambs without defects,
\v 21 and their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings \add as already stipulated\add*.
\v 22 \add Also\add* for your sins, sacrifice one male goat to make \add yourselves right with God\add*, in addition to the regular burnt offerings with their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings.
\p
\v 23 “On the fourth day, \add the sacrifice will be\add* ten young bulls, two rams, fourteen year-old male lambs without defects,
\v 24 and their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings \add as already stipulated\add*.
\v 25 \add Also\add* for your sins, sacrifice one male goat to make \add yourselves right with God\add*, in addition to the regular burnt offerings with their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings.
\p
\v 26 “On the fifth day, \add the sacrifice will be\add* nine young bulls, two rams, fourteen year-old male lambs without defects,
\v 27 and their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings \add as already stipulated\add*.
\v 28 \add Also\add* for your sins, sacrifice one male goat to make \add yourselves right with God\add*, in addition to the regular burnt offerings with their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings.
\p
\v 29 “On the sixth day, \add the sacrifice will be\add* eight young bulls, two rams, fourteen year-old male lambs without defects,
\v 30 and their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings \add as already stipulated\add*.
\v 31 \add Also\add* for your sins, sacrifice one male goat to make \add yourselves right with God\add*, in addition to the regular burnt offerings with their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings.
\p
\v 32 “On the seventh day, \add the sacrifice will be\add* seven young bulls, two rams, fourteen year-old male lambs without defects,
\v 33 and their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings \add as already stipulated\add*.
\v 34 \add Also\add* for your sins, sacrifice one male goat to make \add yourselves right with God\add*, in addition to the regular burnt offerings with their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings.
\p
\v 35 “On the eighth \add and final\add* day, there’s to be \add another\add* sacred assembly. No \add regular\add* work may be done that day.
\v 36 You all must present a young bull, a ram, and seven one-year-old male lambs, \add all\add* unblemished, as a burnt offering that will be a pleasing aroma for Yahweh.
\v 37 Their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings must be \add as already stipulated\add*.
\v 38 \add Also\add* for your sins, sacrifice one male goat to make \add yourselves right with God\add*, in addition to the regular burnt offerings with their \add associated\add* grain and drink offerings.
\p
\v 39 “\add The above are the regulations for what\add* you all must do for Yahweh at the appointed times, in addition to your vows and voluntary offerings, burnt offerings, grain and drink offerings, and your peace offerings.”
\p
\v 40 \add So\add* Moses passed on to the \add Israelis\add* everything that Yahweh had instructed \add him\add*.
\c 30
\s1 Instructions about vows
\p
\v 1 Then Mosheh \add (Moses)\add* \add gave\add* the \add Israeli leaders\add* \add these further instructions from\add* Yahweh,
\v 2 “If a man makes a solemn promise to Yahweh, or makes a binding vow on his own life, he mustn’t dishonour \add what he said\add*—he must follow whatever came out of his mouth.\x + \xo 30:2: \xt Deu 23:21-23; Mat 5:33.\x*
\p
\v 3 If a \add young\add* woman who is \add still living with her parents\add* solemnly promises to Yahweh \add to do something\add*,
\v 4 and \add if\add* her father hears her make the binding vow on her life and he remains silent, then her vow and \add all her obligations\add* will stand.
\v 5 \add However,\add* if her father forbids her \add when\add* he hears her, then that vow and \add its obligations\add* won’t stand, and Yahweh will forgive her, because her father \add stepped in\add*.
\p
\v 6 If she \add gets engaged or married while a vow or thoughtless promise still holds\add*,
\v 7 and her \add (future)\add* husband hears about it and remains silent that day, then her vow and or thoughtless promise will stand.
\v 8 \add However,\add* if her \add (future)\add* husband forbids her \add when\add* he hears her, then that vow and \add its obligations\add* won’t stand, and Yahweh will forgive her.
\p
\v 9 \add If\add* a widow or a woman who has been divorced \add makes a promise, she must do what she promised\add*.
\p
\v 10 \add If a married woman\add* makes a solemn promise, or makes a binding vow on her own life,
\v 11 and her husband hears about it \add but\add* says nothing and doesn’t forbid her, then her vow and \add all her obligations\add* will stand.
\v 12 \add However,\add* if he actually nullifies it when he hears about it, any promise that she pronounced or binding vow on her life, won’t stand. Her husband has nullified them and Yahweh will forgive her,
\v 13 \add so\add* every vow and its obligations can either be nullified or confirmed by her husband.
\v 14 If her husband has stayed silent for \add several days\add*, that will confirm all her vows and/or obligations because he \add said nothing\add*.
\v 15 \add However,\add* if he \add cancels\add* them \add sometime\add* after he’d heard about them, then he will bear her guilt.
\p
\v 16 Those are the instructions that Yahweh \add gave\add* Mosheh \add about promises\add* between a man and his wife, \add and\add* between a father and his \add unmarried\add* daughter \add living at home\add*.
\c 31
\s1 Avenging the Midyanites
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*,
\v 2 “Avenge the Midyanites for what they did to \add you\add* \add Israelis\add*. After that, you’ll \add go to join your ancestors\add*.”
\p
\v 3 \add So\add* Mosheh told the people, “Equip some of your men to battle against Midyan to \add execute\add* Yahweh’s vengeance on \add them\add*—
\v 4 one thousand men from each tribe to go to war.”
\p
\v 5 \add So\add* a thousand men were conscripted from each tribe—twelve thousand equipped for battle
\v 6 and Mosheh sent them off to war. The priest Pinehas (Eleazar’s son) went with them, taking some sacred objects as well as the signal trumpets.
\v 7 Then they fought Midyan just as Yahweh had commanded Mosheh, and they killed every male.
\v 8 \add Among them,\add* they killed five Midyan kings: Evi, Rekem, Tsur, Hur, and Reva, in addition to Beor’s son Bileam \add (Balaam)\add*.
\p
\v 9 The \add Israelis\add* took the Midyan women and children captive, and took all their cattle, \add sheep and goats\add*, and all their \add possessions as plunder\add*,
\v 10 then they burnt down all their cities and houses and camps.
\v 11 They took all the spoil and plunder including the people and animals back,
\v 12 and brought it to Mosheh and the priest Eleazar, and to the \add assembled Israelis\add* who were \add all still\add* camped on the Moav plains beside the Yarden river opposite Yeriho \add (Jericho)\add*.
\s1 Purifying the returning warriors
\p
\v 13 Mosheh and the priest Eleazar and all the \add Israeli\add* leaders left the camp to meet them,
\v 14 \add but\add* Mosheh was angry at the top army leaders who were coming back from the battle.
\v 15 “Why did you allow all the women to live?” \add he\add* asked them.
\v 16 “They’re the \add very ones who did what\add* Bileam \add (Balaam)\add* \add suggested to urge the people to be unfaithful\add* to Yahweh at Peor, \add leading to\add* the plague \add that struck\add* Yahweh’s \add people\add*.\x + \xo 31:16: \xt Num 25:1-9.\x*
\v 17 \add So now,\add* kill all the \add boys\add* plus every woman who’s \add slept with a man\add*—
\v 18 \add spare only the young, unmarried girls\add* for yourselves.
\p
\v 19 “Then everyone who’s killed someone or touched a dead body must stay outside the camp for seven days. On the third day, you all must purify yourselves, and \add again\add* on the seventh day \add but this time\add* including your captives.
\v 20 \add Also,\add* you all must purify all your clothes, plus anything \add else\add* made of leather or goats’ hair or wood.”
\p
\v 21 Then the priest Eleazar told the \add warriors\add* who’d gone to battle, “This is what Yahweh has instructed Mosheh:
\v 22 Only the gold, silver, bronze, iron, tin, and lead,
\v 23 must pass through fire to make it ‘clean’. Nevertheless, it must still be purified with the \add special\add* purifying water, along with anything that wouldn’t \add handle\add* the fire.
\v 24 On the seventh day, you all must wash your clothes and then you’ll be ‘clean’ and \add be allowed to reenter\add* the camp.
\s1 Dividing the plunder
\p
\v 25 Then Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*,
\v 26 “You and the priest Eleazar and the \add tribal leaders\add* must \add list all\add* the plunder \add including both\add* human and animals that were taken captive.
\v 27 Then you must divide \add it all\add* out \add equally between the two groups\add*: those who went out to battle, and all \add the rest of\add* the community.
\v 28 \add Set aside\add* a tribute for Yahweh from \add the plunder of\add* the \add warriors\add* who fought in the battle: one from every five-hundred \add captive\add* people, and \add the same\add* from the cattle and donkeys, and from the \add sheep and goats\add*.
\v 29 Half of that must be given to the priest Eleazar as the contribution to Yahweh.
\v 30 Then from the half \add of the plunder\add* \add given\add* to the \add community\add*, take one from every fifty \add captive\add* people, and \add the same\add* from the cattle and donkeys, and from the \add sheep and goats\add* and other animals. That’s to be given to the Levites because they’re the ones who look after Yahweh’s residence.”
\v 31 \add So\add* Mosheh and the priest Eleazar did what Yahweh had told them to do.
\p
\v 32 The remaining plunder \add after the slaughter of the boys and the married women\add* from what the warriors had brought back was: 675,00 sheep,
\v 33 72,000 cattle,
\v 34 61,000 donkeys,
\v 35 and 32,000 girls \add who hadn’t been married\add*.
\v 36 The \add warriors who’d fought\add* got: 337,500 sheep,
\v 37 \add less\add* 675 that were given to Yahweh \add as his tribute\add*.
\v 38 The cattle were 36,000 \add less\add* 72 for Yahweh.
\v 39 There were 30,500 donkeys \add less\add* Yahweh’s tribute of sixty-one.
\v 40 The \add girls and young women\add* were 16,000 \add less\add* 32 for Yahweh.
\v 41 \add So\add* Mosheh gave Yahweh’s contribution to the priest Eleazar as Yahweh had \add instructed\add* Mosheh.
\p
\v 42 The half for the \add community\add* that Mosheh had divided off from the \add warriors\add*
\v 43 was: 337,500 sheep,
\v 44 36,000 cattle,
\v 45 30,500 donkeys,
\v 46 and 16,000 \add girls who hadn’t been married\add*.
\v 47 From that half for the \add community\add*, Mosheh took one from every fifty people and animals, and gave it to the Levites who serve in Yahweh’s tent, just as Yahweh had \add instructed\add* Mosheh.
\p
\v 48 Then the \add top army\add* officers (the commanders over thousands, and the commanders over hundreds), went to Mosheh
\v 49 and \add informed\add* \add him\add*, “\add We,\add* your servants have \add counted the soldiers who were under us,\add* and \add none of our men are\add* missing,
\v 50 \add so\add* we’ve brought an offering to Yahweh: every man who found \add something\add* gold \add like\add* an armlet or bracelets, signet ring or earring, or necklaces \add has donated it\add* to \add make us right with\add* Yahweh.”
\v 51 \add So\add* Mosheh and the priest Eleazar took those \add crafted\add* gold items from them,
\v 52 and the total contribution of gold \add offered\add* to Yahweh by the commanders of thousands and of hundreds \add weighed around 190 kilograms\add*.
\v 53 Each of the \add warriors\add* had taken \add their own\add* plunder,
\v 54 and Mosheh and the priest Eleazar took the gold from the commanders of thousands and of hundreds, and brought it to the \add sacred\add* tent as a memorial for the \add Israelis\add* \add in front\add* of Yahweh.
\c 32
\s1 The tribes who stayed east of Yarden
\r (Deu. 3:12-22)
\p
\v 1 The \add people\add* from the Reuven and Gad \add tribes\add* \add had amassed\add* \add a lot of\add* livestock, and they \add noticed\add* that the Yazer and Gilead \add regions\add* \add were very suitable\add* for livestock.
\v 2 \add So\add* \add their leaders\add* went to Mosheh and the priest Eleazar and the \add community leaders\add* to say,
\v 3 \add The regions of\add* Atarot, Divon, Yazer, Nimrah, Heshbon, Elealeh, Sevam, Nevo, and Beon
\v 4 are \add in\add* the land \add here\add* that Yahweh has \add handed over to\add* \add us Israelis\add*. It’s \add ideal\add* for livestock, and \add we,\add* your servants, \add raise\add* livestock.
\v 5 If we’ve \add earnt\add* your favour, let this land be given to your servants for \add us to own\add*, \add rather than forcing us\add* to cross over the Yarden \add river with all the other tribes\add*.”
\p
\v 6 “It wouldn’t be right for your \add fellow Israelis\add* to go to war \add while\add* you all \add just\add* stay here,” Mosheh told them.
\v 7 “\add So\add* why do you discourage \add Israeli enthusiasm\add* for crossing over into the land that Yahweh has given them?
\v 8 Your parents did that at Kadesh-Barnea when I sent them \add in\add* to \add survey\add* the land.\x + \xo 32:8-9: \xt Num 13:17-33.\x*
\v 9 They went as far as the Eshkol \add valley\add* and they saw the land, \add yet\add* they discouraged the \add people from\add* entering the land that Yahweh had given them.
\v 10 Yahweh \add got very angry\add* that day, and \add promised\add*,
\v 11 ‘From the men who came out of Egypt, no man who’s twenty or older will see the land which I promised to Abraham, Yitshak \add (Isaac)\add*, and Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*, because they’re not \add fully with\add* me.
\v 12 \add Only\add* Yefunneh’s son Kalev \add (Caleb)\add* and Nun’s son Yehoshua \add (Joshua)\add* \add will enter\add* because they \add have believed\add* me.’
\v 13 \add So\add* Yahweh \add got angry with\add* Yisrael, and made \add us\add* wander in the wilderness for forty years until that generation was \add eliminated\add* who had \add been evil as per Yahweh’s judgement\add*.
\v 14 \add Now look here!\add* You’re \add standing in front of me\add* \add just\add* like your parents—a brood of \add disobedient\add* people who’ll make Yahweh more angry with you than he was with your parents!
\v 15 If you all turn away from following him, he’ll \add abandon\add* you all in the wilderness again, and you will have destroyed this \add nation\add*.”
\p
\v 16 \add However, they stepped\add* closer to him and said, “\add First\add* we’ll build pens for our animals, and build cities for our \add families\add* \add here\add*.
\v 17 Then we’ll equip ourselves for war, \add to go ahead of the rest\add* of Yisrael until we’ve brought them into their place. \add Meanwhile\add* our \add families\add* will live in those fortified cities because \add there’ll still be threats from\add* those who live in \add this region\add*.
\v 18 We won’t return to our \add homes\add* until every \add Israeli\add* is in possession of his inheritance.
\v 19 We won’t take any land \add there\add* on the other side of the Yarden \add river\add* or beyond because this \add will be\add* our inheritance here on the eastern side.”
\p
\v 20 “If you’re \add going to do that\add*,” Mosheh \add responded\add*, “then you all must equip yourselves to \add fight battles for\add* Yahweh,
\v 21 and all of \add your\add* \add armed warriors\add* must cross the Yarden \add to serve\add* Yahweh until he’s driven his enemies out \add ahead of him\add*.
\v 22 \add Once\add* the land is subdued \add before\add* Yahweh, then you all can return. You’ll be free of obligation from Yahweh and from Yisrael, and this land \add here\add* will be your possession \add from\add* Yahweh.
\v 23 \add However\add*, if you all don’t \add help the rest of us\add*, you will be disobeying Yahweh, and \add your disobedience\add* will \add catch up with you\add*.
\v 24 \add So go ahead and\add* build your cities for your \add families\add*, and pens for your flocks, and \add do what you’ve committed to\add*.”
\p
\v 25 “Your servants will do what you’ve said,” \add confirmed\add* the \add leaders of\add* the Reuven and Gad tribes.
\v 26 “Our wives and children, and our livestock and all our animals will remain in cities here in the Gilead \add region\add*,
\v 27 \add but\add* we’ll equip ourselves for battle and to cross \add the river\add* to battle for Yahweh just as my master has spoken.”
\p
\v 28 \add So\add* Mosheh \add gave instructions\add* about them to the priest Eleazar, Nun’s son Yehoshua, and the \add Israeli tribal leaders\add*,\x + \xo 32:28-32: \xt Josh 1:12-15.\x*
\v 29 telling them, “If the \add men from Gad and Reuven tribes\add* cross over the Yarden with you \add and equipped ready to fight for\add* Yahweh and that land \add is conquered\add*, then you must give them the Gilead \add region for them to own\add*.
\v 30 \add However,\add* if they don’t cross over with \add the rest of\add* you, then \add they’ll have to accept\add* land \add to own\add* \add there\add* in Kanaan \add (Canaan)\add*.”
\p
\v 31 “What Yahweh has told you, \add his\add* servants, that’s what we’ll do,” the \add leaders of the Gad and Reuven tribes responded\add*.
\v 32 We’ll \add send armed men across\add* to Kanaan, equipped to fight for Yahweh. \add However,\add* our inheritance to own will be \add here\add* on this side of the Yarden \add river\add*.”
\p
\v 33 \add So\add* Mosheh gave \add that region\add* to the tribes of Reuben and Gad, the half-tribe of Yosef’s son Menashsheh, \add encompassing\add* the kingdoms of the Amorite King Sihon and the Bashan’s King Og, plus the surrounding territories.
\v 34 The Gadites rebuilt Divon, Atarot, Aroer,
\v 35 Atrot-Shofan, Yazer, Yogbehah,
\v 36 Beyt-Nimrah, and Beyt-Haran—\add all\add* fortified cities with pens for their flocks.
\v 37 The Reuvenites rebuilt Heshbon, Elealeh, Kiriatayim,
\v 38 Nevo, Baal-Meon, and Sibmah, \add but\add* they \add renamed\add* \add some\add* of the cities.
\p
\v 39 The descendants of Menashsheh’s son Makir went to Gilead and captured it—driving out the Amorites who \add lived there\add*.
\v 40 \add So\add* Mosheh gave Gilead to Menashsheh’s son Makir, and \add his clan\add* lived there.
\v 41 Menashsheh’s \add other\add* son Yair went and captured \add the Amorite\add* villages and named them ‘Yair’s Towns’ \add (or ‘Havvot-Yair’)\add*.
\v 42 \add A man named\add* Novah went and captured Kenat and its villages, and renamed it to ‘Novah’ after himself.
\c 33
\s1 The journey legs from Egypt to Sinai
\p
\v 1 \add The following\add* are \add the details\add* of the \add stages of Yisrael’s journeys\add* \add starting from\add* when they exited Egypt \add tribe-by-tribe\add* under Mosheh and Aharon’s leadership.
\v 2 Mosheh, \add acting on Yahweh’s instructions\add*, had written down their \add departure points\add*, so these were \add the legs of\add* their journeys:
\p
\v 3 The day after \add they celebrated\add* the ‘pass-over’ \add (around the end of March)\add*, they left Rameses city, raising \add one fist\add* in full view of all Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*.
\v 4 \add Meanwhile\add*, the Egyptians were burying all their oldest sons who’d been struck down by Yahweh \add who had\add* \add also\add* \add totally humiliated\add* their gods.
\p
\v 5 After leaving Rameses, the \add Israelis\add* \add went\add* to Sukkot and camped \add there\add*.
\v 6 Then they left Sukkit and camped at Etam at the edge of the wilderness.
\v 7 \add After\add* Etam, they turned back to Pi-Hahirot (opposite Baal-Tsefon) and camped \add facing\add* Migdal.
\v 8 Then they left Pi-Hahirot and walked through the middle of the sea into the Etam wilderness and camped at Marah.
\v 9 From Marah, they went to Eylim which had twelve springs with seventy palm trees \add around them\add*, and they camped there.
\v 10 \add After\add* Eylam, they camped beside the Red Sea
\v 11 before leaving the sea and camping in the Sin wilderness.\f + \fr 33:11 \ft Note that this is located in the southwestern Sinai Peninsula (between Eylim and Mt. Sinai), and different from the Tsin \+add (Zin)\+add* wilderness (which is located in the northern Negev desert, near Kadesh-Barnea).\f*
\v 12 \add Travelling from there,\add* they camped at Dofkah,
\v 13 and then from there, at Alush.
\v 14 \add After leaving\add* Alush, they camped at Refidim \add but\add* they didn’t have water there to drink.
\v 15 \add When\add* they left Refidim, they camped in the Sinai wilderness.
\s1 The journey legs in the wilderness
\p
\v 16 From the Sinai wilderness, they went to Kivot-Hattaavah and camped \add there\add*.
\v 17 \add When\add* they left Kivot-Hattaavah, they camped at Hatserot,
\v 18 and then from there, at Ritmah.
\v 19 From Ritmah, they \add went to\add* Rimmon-Perets to camp,
\v 20 and after that, on to Livnah.
\v 21 Then they left Livnah and camped at Rissah,
\v 22 \add before moving on from there to\add* camp at Kehelatah.
\v 23 From Kehelatah, they camped at Mt. Shefer,
\v 24 then they left \add the mountain\add* and camped at Haradah.
\v 25 \add When\add* they left Haradah, they camped at Makhelot,
\v 26 and after that, on to Tahat.
\v 27 From Tahat, they camped at Terah,
\v 28 and then from Terah, they went to Mitkah to camp.
\v 29 \add After\add* Mitkah, they camped at Hashmonah,
\v 30 and \add next after that\add*, they camped at Moserot.
\v 31 Then they left Moserot and camped at Bene-Yaakan.
\v 32 From Bene-Yaakan, they \add went to\add* Hor-Haggidgad and camped \add there\add*,
\v 33 then they left and camped at Yotbatah.
\v 34 Then they left Yotbatah and camped at Avronah.
\v 35 From Avronah, they \add went to\add* Etsyon-Gever and camped \add there\add*,
\v 36 then they left and camped in the Tsin \add (Zin)\add* wilderness, i.e., at Kadesh.
\v 37 Then they left Kadesh and camped at Mt. Hor by the border with Edom.
\p
\v 38 Aharon \add (Aaron)\add* the priest \add climbed\add* Mt. Hor \add following Yahweh’s instructions\add*, and then died there on the 5th of the first month, forty years after the \add Israelis\add* had left Egypt.\x + \xo 33:38: \xt Num 20:22-28; Deu 10:6; 32:50.\x*
\v 39 \add He\add* was 123 years old when he died \add there\add* on Mt. Hor.
\p
\v 40 \add Meanwhile,\add* the Canaanite king of Arad who lived in the Negev in Kanaan, heard that the \add Israelis\add* were coming.
\p
\v 41 \add The Israelis\add* left Mt. Hor and camped at Tsalmonah.
\v 42 \add When\add* they left Tsalmonah, they camped at Punon,
\v 43 and \add after that\add*, on to Ovot.
\v 44 \add From\add* Ovot, they \add went on\add* to Iyey-Haavarim at the Moav border.
\v 45 Then they left \add there\add* and camped at Divon-Gad,
\v 46 \add before going on to\add* camp at Almon-Divlatayim.
\v 47 \add From there,\add* they \add went into\add* the Avarim mountains and camped \add facing\add* Nevo.
\v 48 \add After leaving\add* the Avarim mountains, they \add reached\add* the Moav plains by the Yarden \add (Jordan) river\add* \add opposite\add* Yeriho \add (Jericho)\add*.
\v 49 They camped \add beside\add* the \add river\add* from Beyt-Hayshimot to Avel-Shittim \add there\add* on the Moav plains.
\p
\v 50 Then Yahweh spoke to Mosheh \add there\add* on the Moav plains beside the Yarden \add opposite\add* Yeriho,
\v 51 “Tell the \add Israelis\add* that you’re all about to cross the Yahweh to enter Canaan.
\v 52 Then you all must \add drive all the land’s inhabitants out ahead of you\add*, and destroy all their carved images and cast metal images, and all their \add hilltop shrines\add*.
\v 53 Take the land from there and start to live there, because I’ve given \add it\add* to all of you to own.
\v 54 \add Use lots\add* to divide the land up for your clans. \add The larger groups must get more than the smaller groups\add*, then \add whatever the lot gives, that will be the area to be given within the land for that ancestral tribe\add*.\x + \xo 33:54: \xt Num 26:54-56.\x*
\p
\v 55 If you don’t \add drive out the current inhabitants\add*, then they’ll become like barbs in your eyes and thorns in your sides, and they’ll harass you all \add when you live there\add*.
\v 56 \add If that happens,\add* then I’ll \add give you all the punishment\add* that I intended for them.”
\c 34
\s1 The boundaries within Canaan
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*,
\v 2 “Tell the \add people\add* that you’re all about to enter Canaan—the land that will become your inheritance. \add The boundaries will be\add*:
\p
\v 3 “The \bd southern\bd* border will extend from the Tsin wilderness along the Edom border across to the Salt \add (Dead)\add* Sea on the east,
\v 4 cross south of the Scorpion Pass, continue to Tsin, and go south of Kadesh-Barnea. Then it will go on to Hatsar-Addar and proceed to Atsmon,
\v 5 From Atsmon \add it will extend west\add* to the riverbed at the border with Egypt, and then across to the \add Mediterranean\add* Sea.
\p
\v 6 “The \bd western\bd* border will be the \add Mediterranean\add* sea.
\p
\v 7 “The \bd northern\bd* border will start at the \add Mediterranean\add* sea and extend west to Mt. Hor,
\v 8 and then on to Levo-Hamat and onward to Tsedad.
\v 9 \add From there\add* the border will extend to Zifron, and it will end at Hatsar-Eynan, \add completing\add* the northern border.
\p
\v 10 “The \bd eastern\bd* border will begin at Hatsar-Eynan and extend \add south\add* to Shefam,
\v 11 then go downhill to Rivlah east of Ayin, then along the \add hills\add* to the east of Lake Galilee \add (Heb. Kinneret)\add*.
\v 12 Then the border will extend \add south\add* along the Yarden \add River\add* and \add end at\add* the Salt \add (Dead)\add* Sea.
\p “Those will be your \add country’s\add* borders.”
\p
\v 13 Then Mosheh \add continued\add*, “That will be the land that \add must be distributed\add* by lot. It’ll be given by Yahweh as an inheritance for the nine tribes and the Menashsheh half-tribe\x + \xo 34:13: \xt Num 26:52-56.\x*
\v 14 \add as\add* the Reuven and Gad tribes and the Menashsheh half-tribe have already received their inheritance.
\v 15 \add Yes,\add* the \add other\add* two and a half tribes have taken up their inheritance on the eastern side of the Yarden \add river\add* across from Yeriho \add (Jericho)\add*.
\s1 The teachers egpepamaaren of land
\p
\v 16 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 17 “These are the men who will \add distribute\add* the land: the priest Eleazar and Nun’s son Yehoshua \add (Joshua)\add*,
\v 18 as well as one leader from each tribe to allocate the land that will be their inheritance.
\v 19 Those \add tribe\add* leaders are:
\li1 From Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*, Yefunneh’s son Kalev \add (Caleb)\add*,
\li1
\v 20 From Shimeon, Ammihud’s son Shemuel,
\li1
\v 21 From Benyamin, Kislon’s son Elidad,
\li1
\v 22 From Dan, Yogli’s son Bukki,
\li1
\v 23 From Menashsheh, Efod’s son Hanniyel,
\li1
\v 24 From Efrayim, Shiftan’s son Kemuel,
\li1
\v 25 From Zevulun, Parnach’s son Elizafan,
\li1
\v 26 From Yissakar, Azzan’s son Paltiel,
\li1
\v 27 From Asher, Shelomi’s son Ahihud,
\li1
\v 28 From Naftali, Ammihud’s son Pedahel.”
\p
\v 29 \add The above\add* are \add the men\add* that Yahweh \add put in charge of dividing up\add* Kanaan as the inheritance for the \add Israelis\add*.
\c 35
\s1 Cities for the Levites
\p
\v 1 \add While\add* they were there on the Moav plains beside the Yarden \add river\add*, Yahweh told Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*.\x + \xo 35:1-8: \xt Josh 21:1-42.\x*
\v 2 “Tell the \add Israelis\add* that out of the land that they’ll \add own\add*, they must give the Levites cities for them to live in, \add as well as\add* some pastureland around \add those\add* cities.
\v 3 The cities will be for them to live in, and that pastureland will be for their herds and their flocks, and for their other animals.
\v 4 The pastureland must extend out half a kilometre around the walls of the Levites cities.
\v 5 Then going out a kilometre \add in each compass direction\add*, that will also be their land.\f + \fr 35:5 \ft It’s not exactly clear what different activities would occur in these two rings of land, but remember that as much food as possible and animals would have to be brought into the city as soon as the residents received news of an approaching army.\f*
\v 6 The Levites \add must be given forty-two cities to live in, plus\add* you all must \add designate\add* six refuge cities so that if someone accidentally kills another, they can flee to the refuge city.
\v 7 \add That would make a total of\add* forty-eight cities, plus their pasturelands, to be given to the Levites.
\v 8 The larger tribes must give more cities than the smaller tribes, according to the area that they inherit.”
\s1 The refuge cities
\r (Deu. 19:1-13; Josh. 20:1-9)
\p
\v 9 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,\x + \xo 35:9-28: \xt Deu 19:2-4; Josh 20:1-9.\x*
\v 10 “Tell the \add Israelis\add* that when you cross the Yarden \add river\add* \add to enter\add* Kanaan,
\v 11 you all must choose some cities to become ‘refuge cities’ \add so that\add* if someone accidentally kills another person, they can flee there.
\v 12 The cities will be places to stay safe from \add being avenged\add* \add by the relatives\add* until the killer can \add be formally tried\add*.
\v 13 You all must \add allocate\add* six refuge cities—
\v 14 three on the eastern side of the Yarden, and there on the western side in Kanann.
\v 15 Both \add Israelis\add* and \add foreigners living in the country\add* can flee to \add any of\add* those six cities—anyone who kills \add another\add* person by accident.
\p
\v 16 “However, if someone strikes \add another person\add* with \add a metal object\add* and they die, then that person is a murderer, and murderers must be \add executed\add*.
\v 17 \add Similarly,\add* anyone who strikes \add another person\add* when holding a \add rock or\add* stone, then that person is a murderer, and murderers must be \add executed\add*.
\v 18 \add Again,\add* if someone strikes \add another person\add* with a piece of wood, then that person is a murderer, and murderers must be \add executed\add*.
\v 19 The \add relative who\add* is avenging the \add spilt\add* blood must \add execute the murderer as soon as he finds them\add*.
\p
\v 20 “If someone pushes \add another person\add* in hatred, or lies in wait and then throws something at them,
\v 21 or angrily strikes them with their hand, and then they die, \add it must be regarded as murder,\add* and when the avenger of their blood finds the murderer, he must \add execute\add* them.
\p
\v 22 “\add But\add* if someone pushes \add another person\add* without any hateful \add intent\add*, or throws something at them without lying in wait,
\v 23 or drops a rock without \add noticing\add* someone, and they die \add but\add* they weren’t \add that person’s\add* enemy and no harm was intended,
\v 24 then the community must judge between the \add one who killed\add* and the avenger \add of the dead person\add*, in accordance with these regulations.
\v 25 \add If the one who killed is declared innocent\add*, then the community must rescue them from the avenger and return them to the refuge city that they’d fled to, and \add that accidental killer\add* must live there until after the death of the high priest (who had been anointed with sacred oil).
\v 26 \add However,\add* if they then ever left the refuge city that they’d fled to,
\v 27 and the avenger found them outside the city boundary, then \add that relative of the dead person\add* is permitted to kill that person and won’t be accountable for their blood.
\v 28 \add That’s\add* because the \add one who killed\add* must remain in that city until the death of the high priest—they can only return to \add their family home\add* after the high priest’s death.
\v 29 You all must \add follow\add* these regulations through the generations no matter where you live.
\p
\v 30 “\add If\add* someone murders \add another\add* person, they’re to be executed if there’s evidence from witnesses (\add plural,\add* not just one witness).
\v 31 That sentence \add can’t be changed to a fine and/or a payment to the deceased’s family\add*—\add the murderer\add* \em must\em* be executed.
\v 32 \add Similarly for the accidental killer who fled to a refuge city\add*, they can’t \add elect to pay a fine and/or pay compensation\add* in order to be able to return \add home\add* before the high priest’s death.
\v 33 You mustn’t profane the land that you’re all going to \add by tolerating murder\add*, because \add human\add* blood pollutes the ground, and you all can’t \add restore the land with any sacrifice\add*—only by the blood of the one who shed \add someone else’s\add* blood.
\v 34 You mustn’t profane the land that you’ll all be living in because I’ll also be living in it, as I will live among \add you\add* \add Israelis\add*.”
\c 36
\s1 Women inheriting property
\p
\v 1 \add Now\add* the leaders of the Gilead clans (\add Gilead was\add* the son of Makir, son of Menashsheh, one of Yosef’s sons) approached Mosheh and the \add Israeli\add* leaders
\v 2 and said, “Yahweh commanded my master to \add distribute\add* the land by lot as an inheritance \add for the people\add*, and my master was \add also\add* commanded by Yahweh to give our brother Tselofehad’s inheritance to his daughters.\x + \xo 36:2: \xt Num 27:7.\x*
\v 3 \add However, if\add* they \add ended up\add* \add being married by men from other\add* tribes, then their inheritance would \add pass from our tribe to their husbands’ tribes, so we’d end up with less land as our tribal\add* inheritance.
\v 4 Then when Yisrael celebrates the Jubilee \add Year\add*, then that inheritance will be added to the inheritance of \add their husbands’\add* tribes, and be deducted from the inheritance of our \add ancestral\add* tribe.”
\p
\v 5 Then Mosheh \add gave a ruling\add* to the \add Israelis\add* \add in accordance with what Yahweh had told him\add*, “These \add Yosefite men\add* are correct.
\v 6 Yahweh’s \add command\add* to Tselofehad’s daughters is that \add each of you may marry whoever you want as long as it’s someone from your own\add* tribe.
\v 7 That way, land \add in Yisrael\add* won’t \add move\add* from tribe to tribe, because \add it will always stay as part of\add* the inheritance \add given to that\add* tribe.
\v 8 \add Any woman who inherits land can only marry someone from her own\add* tribe, so that the people will \add always\add* \add retain ownership of their tribal\add* inheritance.
\v 9 \add That\add* inheritance mustn’t pass from tribe to tribe, but each \add Israeli\add* tribe must keep hold of its inheritance.”
\p
\v 10 So Tselofehad’s daughters obeyed what Yahweh had told Mosheh,
\v 11 and the \add five\add* daughters (Mahlah, Tirtsah, Hoglah, Milkah, and Noah) married their \add cousins on their father’s side\add*.
\v 12 \add The men they married\add* were from the Menashsheh tribe (Yosef’s son), so \add their land continued to belong to their father’s family and\add* tribe.
\p
\v 13 \add All the above\add* were the commands and regulations that Yahweh ordered Mosheh to tell the \add Israelis\add*, \add while they were camped\add* on the Moav plains beside the Yarden \add river\add* \add opposite\add* Yeriho \add (Jericho)\add*.
